\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid6114892 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Could I have your name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. Mr - I am Mr Mulligan and I am aged - sixty-nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 So you were born in 1902?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 '02.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Could you tell me where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well I was born in Hackney, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
North London{\*\xmlclose}. Do you know - Hackney?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Where about in Hackney would it be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 There's a little place called Clarence -
 Terrace. Which was - just a small terrace in a cul-de-sac and - very very old houses you know, the street doors were straight onto the street, no front gardens, anything like that. And - I can't think how many rooms there was but there was quite a big fa
mily of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 How many were there of you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Thirteen - all together. Yes. Yes, I - I don't remember all - all of them but - I remember eleven - of the thirteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Where did you come in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 I came last but one, I came - the twelf
th, I was the twelfth in the - in the family.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Do you know roughly when the eldest was born then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Ah - now you're asking something. Yes, 1881. My brother - oldest brother.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 The one after you was born one or two years later than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 One after me? Two years. Two years. Two years. Yes. Two years. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 How many brothers were there then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
I had - altogether - I had - let's see - seven. Seven brothers. Seven brothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 But two of the brothers didn't live?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. Well they're all dead now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 But I mean when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Yes. Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
By the time you can remember you'd moved from the house where you were born had you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 I - from - no, I hadn't moved from the house, the time t
hat I can remember, still living there and - we lived there - I lived there for about - six years after I was born. And - we just went to another house which was easy in those days to get a house in fact they were two a penny. And - if you ever got tired 
o
f your house you were living say well, another one to let, just a few streets away, well - we'll have that one you see. And the landlord in those days were - was - was very glad to get an agreement that you would take the house on a lease for two years or
 
three years, doing all your own repairs and that you see. Although - we thought - land - you know land - house owners then were landlords, used to call them - very rich people. But - they were to our standards really. But it was - it was quite - quite eas
y to move then from one house to another you know, plenty of moves. Which I experienced.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You did move several times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Why do you think the family did move when they moved?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well - growing up you see and - then - wanted 
more rooms, somebody - one of 'em'd want a separate room or - another room. Then - and get a bigger house, the family was getting bigger, you naturally wanted a bigger house. And then the - boys, you know, started courting, bringing their young ladies hom
e and that. Wanted a - somewhere to go, one room to do their courting. But - the sisters, well they weren't allowed to have young men. Father wouldn't allow it. No. Not in those days. No, that was very funny, very strict like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You mean they asked to bring them home and he said no?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh he - he just wouldn't let them have a - a young man. Used to get into trouble if - they'd been out with a young man. And yet the boys, they could go out with young ladies and bring them home. Oh yes, funny ideas my father had like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Do you know roughly speaking when your father was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well, he died in 19 - 14 and he was fifty-five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did he come from Hackney or London?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. He came from Ireland. Hence the name Mulligan. And - he came fro
m a - County Wicklow. A - a place called Averca, County Wicklow, Ireland. And - he came over here, with his brother, his brother Jack, to find work and - he found work here, he was a shoemaker by trade, his brother was as well but - his brother went off t
o America and then he came back to England. He died in England. The same as my father.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Had he always been a shoemaker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh he'd always been a shoemaker as far as I - I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 He didn't have any part time jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No part time job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was he working on his own account?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. He wasn't working on his own account. Working for a firm, but - in those days they used to be outworkers, out door workers, people used to work in their own homes, you see. And - probably many of them employed p
eople - in their own homes you see. They used to have - a room set aside - for a workshop. And father used to work at home and the boys used to work at home with him. And in fact nearly all the family were in the shoe trade. I got - I got into it eventual
l
y. And - I - I - I - my aunt as well, she was a - in the shoe trade, she used to work at home. And I remember - I used to go around to her house quite a lot, and she used to do - machine the uppers, the shoe uppers you see. And they used to get - three an
d
 sixpence per gross, for stitching - machine - shoe uppers together. It was absolute slavery. And they'd work 'til midnight and past midnight to get a living. And I - I can remember it - see it now quite clearly, all the - all these uppers, shoe uppers, b
e
ing machined and all run off a machine, all joined together, not time to cut them apart. Then you finished one you let the thread - go straight on you see until perhaps the shuttle runs out, then you've got to re - refill your shuttle. It was absolute sla
very. And three and sixpence per gross. And - they reckoned, you know, that was good pay then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You had to help did you yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No, I didn't - I didn't help - I - I never helped, I used to watch. I - I was too young, really. To do anything for t
hem. But mother used to help my father. She used to stitch the shoes. 'Cos they're all had down. My father was a court shoemaker. He made for Royalty you see. Through a firm, through a West End firm as a rule. And - he was a real - real good mechanic. Was
 
absolutely perfectionist. And - he - taught my brothers the trade you see and they had to work to his standards, which was rather difficult to keep up. 'Cos if they got one stitch in a shoe longer than another, they were for it, they - they knew it. And -
 but he was a - a real good workman. And - he made the Coronation shoes for Queen Mary, at the Coronation of King George VI - V. Made her shoes. And - for all Royalty he used to make. And I followed in his footsteps.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 That's the only job you've done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Later on. Yes. Really. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was he ever short of work then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Not to - not to my - remembrance - there was times - I remember times now - towards 19 - 11, '12, just pre-war, when he was - without work. He was a staunch trade unionist, and he 
was victimized by many firms. Found it rather difficult. And he had to rely on his mates - his union mates to - for - substance you see. But he was a really - a really - out and out union man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 That's rather unusual for someone who wasn't working in a workshop isn't it?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes. But you see - he used to belong to a club, and he was a - he was a Radical. In those days there - there was only Conservatives and Radicals, or Liberals, as we call 'em now. And he was a Radical. He used to belong to this club
 and - many of his mates in the shoe trade - they belonged to the same club, that is how he - got a connection you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was that the Hackney Radical club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
And - there was an epitaph - in a magazine, a Liberal magazine - to him after his death, a
nd - I think I can quite it if you give me a few minutes. Grim death had he no fear of the spirit that's gone, he lived for the good of all men by his actions, his voice and his pen. I remember that. Right from - when I was a - I was about twelve when he 
died. Yes, twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did your mother work apart from helping your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, she was - real housewife. Housewife cum - father's help as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Do you know if she'd worked before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 She was in service. She was in service. I 
- I can remember - she telling me about she was - in service she used to be a cook as well and she used to work at a public house called the Salmon and Ball at Bethnal Green, in - East London. And - she said - she was given a huge lobster to boil. So big 
s
he couldn't get in the saucepan. So she did half at a time. I said to her, mum - which part did you put in first? So she said, oh the tail. I said, why didn't you put the head in first to - to kill it - kill it straight - straight off? It was alive you se
e. And she boiled it alive. It's horrible - it's always - you know, kept in my memory. Whenever I see a lobster I think of that - story. Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 She came from London then did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 She was - she was born in Rotherhithe. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would your father have come over when he was very young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. Oh yes, must have been about eighteen. 'Course - my - eldest brother was - born - when - mum and dad married about eighteen. Only about eighteen when -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Your mother was about the same age was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 She would have been, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 After he died she didn't go out to work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. No. No it was - that was during the first year of the first war - world war. That was - December. 1914. 'Cos - the war was declared in about September, and 
- father went to Woolwich Arsenal into the saddlery shop to work you see. Making saddles you see, where - that's where his craft as a shoemaker - stood him in good - stead. They used to stitch the saddles you see, all - do all leather work. Saddles and st
r
aps. And - he contracted pneumonia. And he died - Boxing Day 1914. On a Boxing Day. I can remember - remember his last words. He was struggling for breath, was fighting for his breath and he said to my mother - my mother - he used to call my mother old wo
m
an, never used to call her by her christian name, Katherine or Kate, he always called her old woman. And he was struggling away and he was saying, old woman, this is a tough bit of leather this is, this is tough. So he imagined he was - stitching - a toug
h piece of leather. And that was - that was his - hard breathing you see. 'Course these sort of things do stick in your mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Do you remember his funeral then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What happened when he died then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh - there was floral tributes from e
verywhere and especially his club mates and - a framed - memorial - notice you know and signed by - all the - most of the members of the - club and the union and that. It was quite a - a big affair. I can remember - he was buried in the Roman Catholic cem
etery, Leytonstone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You didn't have a sort of Irish Wake?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. No. He - he wasn't - he wasn't a religious man. No. He was - well, no, yes he - he was buried in the Roman Catholic - the service was in the Roman Catholic cemetery. But we didn't unde
rstand a word of it. 'Cos it's all in Latin. So we didn't understand what - the service at all. But - my mother was also buried in the same - cemetery, I don't know why really, but -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was there a big sort of tea or something afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes, 
after - funeral, always - always do have - do now, they have part - not party, had a big tea. Oh yes, there was then. Only he was a very generous man. And - I used to think - about as I think now about Christmas time, parties, the house was open. In fact 
i
t was always open - to anybody that came in. But Christmas time especially. And - it earned the nickname the house - we were living in Hackney then, in a road called Aspland Grove, and - I - and - there used to be dozens, literally dozens of people come i
n
 during the day for a drink - and piece of - of mince pie, and evening time the house'd be absolutely packed, they - they never used to go home 'til about four o'clock in the morning. They just slept where they could, I remember sleeping in the passage an
d on the stairs and all that. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would there be sing-songs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. Oh yes, oh all sing - all the children as well got to sing their - do their bit you know, sing something and - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 And did you play games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, not - not many g
ames. Was - was just a - really a - what do you call it, a - just a - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1015488\charrsid10450967 tea party}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967  more like, you know, a {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Boston{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1015488\charrsid10450967 tea party}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
, like that. That's at Christmas, yes. But - but any other time - anybody was, you know - like come in for a drink or a cup of tea or anything like that. The door was always open. Liberty Hall they called it. They called it 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Liberty{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 They would just sort of chat and maybe sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes, that's right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Nothing else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh no. Oh no. No. No. Just really - real neighbourly you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 When your father died did you have to wear mourning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. Yes. Yes, that was a job. Find - buying us - clothes. 'Cos - I mean, we weren't poor. We weren't rich. We weren't in the middle class. Was just in between the middle class and
 lower class. Because - he used to earn fairly good money - for those days, and he used to work hard for it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 But it made it very difficult for your mother when he died?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 They usually used to come from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
country-region}}Belgium{\*\xmlclose}, from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Ostend{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and they're al
l frozen, full of ice. Mind your hands. Oh. Get cold and stiff. And you had to skin 'em, pull - the skin right - right over their heads and pull the skin right off and then cut them up into joints, and sell them. And then - that was usually in the morning
.
 Usually sold out by the afternoon. So afternoons and evening your time was occupied by delivering orders. Same as the butchers. I used to get about four and six for that, or three and six, I can't - not sure now. And tips. I used to get about five bob fo
r
 that. Five bob a week. And I kept that up for a long time until - I left school. From one job to another, almost in the seem sort of thing. And then - fourteen, I left school, and - went into a shoe warehouse. And - that - that was in - see, shoe trade a
gain you see, that's before I learnt shoemaking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 How did you get the job in the shoe warehouse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well my sisters, they used to work outdoors for the shoe firm and they enquired if - I - for me, if there was a vacancy. They said, oh yes, there was 
- vacancy in the warehouse you see. - So I went into to the warehouse. That was during the war. But it was a blind alley job really, because when the war was over - chap whose job I filled, he was fortunate enough to come back from the war, he wanted his 
j
ob back. So - I was redundant then you see. And - I had no job to go to. Things were bad then, there was no - jobs weren't easy to get. There was a great deal of unemployment, people on the dole. It was terrible really. And so - my brother - he said he wo
u
ld take me under his wing and teach me the shoemaking. And he had a bet with my other brothers that he would - teach me in six months. And he won the bet. He did, he taught me in six months. Then I went - branched out on my own. See, I - I went - and - go
t a job at - outdoor worker. And I had a little workshop on my own in - in the house you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 A sort of repair shop you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. No, this was making. Making shoes. Hand - hand made shoes. And they were - made inside out, these shoes. What they c
all turn shoe making. You - you - the - they're made inside out, they're all stitched on the inside you see, and then you turn 'em back the right way out, so the stitches are invisible. You can't see a stitch on the soles to the upper, can't see where the
y
're stitched. And I used to work for West End firms and big firm - but not the big firm, a shop in - Bond Street called Knowles. Shop in Collegiate Street. Do you know that, in - in the West End? Fox and Fox, and Knightsbridge, Harrods, used to work for t
h
em. All out - all out - doors, used to do all out door. And - I made shoes for - Queen of the Belgians, Princes Margaret and Princess - Princess Anne, and other princesses. Not Princess - Princess - Queen Elizabeth, the present Queen - Elizabeth and her s
i
ster. And - and Margaret. Elizabeth and Margaret. And - then - there was a big exhibition on 19 - 19 - what was - what year was the - Empire Exhibition. Anyway, the first Empire Exhibition they had at Wembley. I was working for a firm then named H and H R
a
yne, theatrical shoemakers, and they - gave me the honour of making their exhibition shoes. Made about twenty pair - of show shoes - shoes. Not - not practicable shoes. Couldn't wear them really. 'Cos - some of the heels on the were six inches high, had h
e
els like that, six inches high. And they were - full of jewels, covered with jewels, paste jewels you know. And - used to - I used to take a pride in the work then you know. I used to work for an honour, as they say. Not for a living. I earn very good mon
ey really - for then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You felt it a real pleasure?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes, you did, you really - took a pride in - what you did. Because - you had to do practically everything except make the uppers. The heels were made of wood and you'd have a block of wood, a ro
ugh shaped block of wood. You had to carve that - to - into a slender heel, slender shape - slender curves. And you had to do them - exactly the same, a pair, and they used to take hours. And - not - all that sort of thing you had to do it all yourself. A
nd that - that - that made out take a pride in your work yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Is that very like what your father was making?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Same. Yes. Same - same - same sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you belong to a trade union like him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes, I did belong to the - the - union, the Shoemakers - Union.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 When you were working as a boy in this warehouse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No, not then. Oh no, not then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What exactly were you doing in the warehouse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Packing and dispatching.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 How many other people were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well the
re was only one man working with me, he showed me - you know, he taught me - what to do. And he was an elderly man. And - I used to know - they had a big warehouse, and if the boss came round to me and said, Charlie, I want a pair of so-and-so shoes, I'd 
know just where to put me hands on 'em. Had thousands of pairs of shoes - and we used to make them for other - other firms. Manfield, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Northampton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, Saxone, places like that, we used to make them for them you see. Although their - their name used to go into t
he shoes, into the sock of the shoe, the Saxons Shoe Company Limited, but they were made by Turner Brothers of Hackney, you see. There's only one - one firm I can remember - that was Manfields - who had their socks printed Manfield and Son - made expressl
y by Turner Brothers of Hackney. That's the only firm I can remember who acknowledged that - they were made by Turner Brothers, not their own manufacture.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 How did you get on with this boss, or didn't you see much of him really?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well - which boss?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 In the warehouse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes, I was with him all the time working on the same bench.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 In the warehouse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh the boss. The boss. Oh I'm - oh very well. Very well - with the boss. There was two brothers. And they were real gentlemen you kno
w and - they were very good. Very good they were. But - there you are - the - they didn't take in consideration - my future, after all, although I was hoping that I would - have a future in that job you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Could you have learned a trade while you were in that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh no. No. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 When you say you were working at the same bench, that was with the old man?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh this man who taught you see, the other warehouseman. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What sort of hours did you work, did you have a half day while 
you were there at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Saturday. Saturday half day. Yes. Used to work fifty-eight hours a week. That was fifty - yes, fifty-eight hours a week, and Saturday half day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you enjoy the job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 I did. Oh yes. Yes, I used to like it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 If you'd have been able to stay on at that you would have been quite happy?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes, I'd have been happy I think. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you feel that the family was worse off at the time your father died?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well, I did, you know, just personal feeling you kn
ow, that - I thought father's - you know - father's gone, I'll have to help you see, yet my contribution being very - very small. But - I didn't have to do it, I did it off me own bat you see. I felt like a hero really. I - I was really, what I put up wit
h to - earn a few bob a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Your family didn't have to get any help from outside then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No, not as - not as I recall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Your mother wouldn't have got a pension at all would she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh no. Oh no, nothing like that. No pension like that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 And no sort of charitable help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No. No. There's no public assistance. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 So you didn't notice anything like the food getting a bit thinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Food? Well - now - I was going to mention that. That was during the war. Well food 
was a terrible problem. They had no rationing then like we'd had in this last war, world war. You had to get food where you could. Well - you had - somebody come around to your house say, oh - Mr Jones has got some jam today. Hurry up, you'd have to hurry
 
up, there's a great big queue there. So - all the family would go, or all that was available, to queue up at this shop to get - two ounces of margarine or two ounces of butter you see. The bigger your family the bigger portion you got, but very often you 
were unlucky, because you'd get almost to the door, sold out. Shut on you. Hundreds of people be turned away. And that's a common }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1015488\charrsid10450967 occurrence}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967  every day, you'd go - you'd see a queue and you'd tack yourself on it, quite regardless of what they were selling, y
ou knew they were selling something that was in short supply 'cos everything was in short supply. And so you - you tacked yourself on and - and hoped for the best. Now - I remember - my brother, one of my brothers, he was very - got a Jewish appearance, h
e
 looked really like a Jew, dark and the big nose like I've got, a real - real Jewish appearance and - he said, come on Charlie, he said, we're going up Petticoat Lane. That's round Whitechapel. He said, I know where we can get some jam. So - we went up th
e
re on a Sunday morning. Queuing at the shop. Nearly - lot of Jews, you know, nearly all Jews. Well we got on the queue. We got to the counter. My brother said, Mr Cohen, you know, Mr Cohen, he says, can I have a pound of jam? So - oh yes, he said, I can a
f
ford - yes, I can spare - how about a pound for my liddle brudder? Is that your liddle brudder? Yes. All right, well he can have a pound. And he got away with it like that. You had to get all sorts of dodges you know, get through. That was a terrible prob
lem.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Could you tell me what sort of food you would usually have at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Just plain foods and - and I'll tell you what we used to have a lot of. Dumplings. Suet dumplings. And - my mother used to make about ninety at a time. She had ninety - ninety for us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What would she do with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well serve them up and we'd eat them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Ninety?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes. Between twelve of us. Yes. We did. And - oh we used to have good appetites ten. Ninety dumplings she used to make. And - other food, plain food, but we were never short, we didn't go short of any. We had plain foods but we never went short.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
You never saw your mother having a bit less so the rest of you could have more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh I think she did, I think - I think she - she suffered a lot you
 know, but - realize it now we're older. And - when I think of the way she used to work - for my father, past midnight, by - ordinary oil lamps - all oil lamps they had to work by then, well I used to work by an oil lamp. And - I couldn't now, but - it's 
surprising how you got used to it. And then we went over to incandescent lamps, ordinary gas. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would you have a breakfast in the morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Have a breakfast, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You'd get bread and butter. Yes, or bread and - bread and margarine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was your father always there at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would he have something more?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
He'd usually have an egg or a bit of bacon and that, he - he'd get the main meal - he'd get a bonus usually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What would you usually have for dinner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - stews. Plenty of stews. And - bubble and squeak we used to call it, fried up from Sunday, used to have that Monday you know and - vegetables and potatoes and all that all fried up, used to like that. And - then - dum
plings, you know, puddings. Fruit puddings, currant puddings. Lots of currant puddings we used to get. Yes. And - father - always used to - have a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid1015488\charrsid10450967 nap}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967  - after dinner. Well, he used to sit at the dinner table with his apron on, his working apron, and he use
d to - after dinner he used to lean back in his chair, throw his apron over his head and off he'd go. And my mother used to say to us, 'course when we were kids, ssh, not a sound. You wake dad up and there'd be trouble. We used to be quiet as nice. And - 
and during the mealtimes if we put our elbows on the table we used to get rapped on our elbows - with his knife, he used to get the handle of his knife and bang it on your elbow, make you take your elbows off the table. Taught us table manners.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Like sitting up you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes, sitting up straight and - you know, not slouching down and - putting your elbows on the table like that. He'd be on to you for that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did they let you talk at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. But - not too much. Used to check you if you
 got - talking too much. But there usually - usually were busy reading a newspaper when we were having our meals because that - that was the tablecloth. The tablecloth was made of newspapers - spread on the table.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did they let you choose what you wanted to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh no, you had to have what was given you. If you didn't like it go without.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 If you didn't eat it they didn't bring it back the next meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh no. No. Well - usually, I used to eat it. If the others didn't eat it, didn't want it.
 They used to call me waste up. Although I never got fat, always think. But - they always called me waste dump. Charlie'll eat it if you won't, you know. And I did. And - and - and yet -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You could ask for some more then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes, you could ask fo
r some more. And yet - I'm so delicate you know, as a child, and yet I could always eat - yes. I spent most of my childhood in hospital, in and out. I don't suppose I had - about three years schooling. And I - I left in the top standard. Not - not by meri
t
, just compulsion you see, they had to put - put me up, I keep in one standard for two years, and they - they've got to put me up in the next standard so I - up - up I went you see. In those days there was - what was called a Labour exam, which allowed yo
u
, if you passed it, to leave school at thirteen instead of fourteen. Well all the family went in for that, and all passed. They all left at thirteen. Except me, I - I couldn't - well it was impossible. Couldn't - think - couldn't think of it. But - I've l
earned more since I left school than I ever learnt in school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you each have your set places at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes, usually, yes, yes, we all used to sit in the same place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did your mother serve the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes, mother usually used to serve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would she serve it onto your plate?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Straight out on - on - straight onto your plate out of the saucepan onto your plates. Dole it out you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 When you finished could you leave or did you all have to sit to the end?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, we just 
- got up when we wanted to, we - we weren't taught that - that far, no, manners, you know, and didn't have to ask permission to leave the table. Not then. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What did you have for tea?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh just - plain - bread and jam, butter or margarine and ja
m. If you could get it. But - Sunday was the day when you had - a real good - good dinner you know. Sunday extra, roast and - and - all the - trimmings you know and - lots of gravy and trifle and things like that after - dessert. Sunday was a day you used
 
to look forward to. And then - after - after dinner, the front room was opened. What they called a parlour. That was open once a week, that room, it used to small pretty - musty then that did as well. And - father and boys - the older sons you know, to si
t
 down and play cards and smoke, play - cards all the afternoon, cirb, whist and things like that. And the children, other children by theirself and - we'd play games, ludo, tiddlywinks things like that. And - that always on Sunday. Usually used to go to c
hurch. Sunday school. Yes, Sunday school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Your mother and father wouldn't go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No. He brother - well, me older brothers didn't go either.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were you sent to a Catholic Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. Oh no. No. Ordinary Methodist. No, father - was
n't bit interested in religion at all. Really. He didn't care if he went or not. It's my sisters who insisted on us going really. Yes, two sisters, they're both Sunday school teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 They taught at that Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 They taught at the - Methodist, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you have grace at home at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What about family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Were there any other church activities like a club or anything that you belonged to?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well there was - what we called Band of H
ope. And that was - you had - you did - gym - gymnastics and you had parties. You had prize giving - for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 attendances}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 , Sunday school }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 attendances}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 . And - used to put on plays sometimes you know, sort of - kiddies plays you know, and that - that was - nice. Bu
t - then they used to have - magic lantern shows, what they called magic lantern shows. All stills you know. 'Course like the projectors we have now glorified magic lanterns. And that. I think they were worked by candle, those magic lanterns, candle light
. Used to have very big reflector, I've got an idea it was candlelight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you have a Sunday school outing once a year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes. Sunday school outings, that was a real treat, once a year. Got to - out to Epping way, Chingford and - there used to be 
- there is now, several, what they call retreats, where they put on Sunday school parties. The food and that you know, serve the food. There was Rich Retreat, Guides Retreat and some other retreat, can't think of it now, and - we used to like going there.
 It was usually on a Saturday. And we used to have a real good - food, you know, real good tea. Oh and then we used to go}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 in - open brakes, what we call brakes, they were like big - well something like motor coaches in a way but they were - on solid wheels 
and drawn by horses you see, like the old horse buses in those days. And - all open. There was no cover at all, if it poured with rain you got soaked, you just had covers to put over your lap - your laps you know, waterproof covers but - top part of you u
sed to get soaking wet. But we never used to take any notice of that. Used to love it. Used to go out about eight in the morning and - come home about eight at night. Real good long day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was the Saturday usually different from other days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well - 
like it is now, Saturday seems different now doesn't it to other days really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you have a job or anything on Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well I did. Lots of boys of my age did jobs as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You didn't go to football or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No. No
t then, later on we used to go to - when I was older we used to go and watch football matches, our favourite team you know, the Arsenal and Spurs. Arsenal and Spurs are quite near each other you know, their ground. If they were - Arsenal might be playing 
a
way one week and Spurs the next, or - the other way round you know. Nearly every week when I was older - we used to go and watch - watch them. There's still a lot of - rowdyism even then like there is today. It's quite a common thing to see a spectator wa
lk on the field and punch a player on the nose you see, punch him on the nose or something like that, yes. It's no different today really, it wasn't.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did your mother bake her own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 And she didn't make jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No. All bought.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What about pickles?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 All bought. Shop stuff.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 She didn't make any homemade wines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. Oh no. Nothing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did they grow vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Never used to do that in London you know. Not in London. No. I - I can't remember anybody doing it in London, mostly country. Well it - it used to be - during the war they started what they call allotments. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 That's the first world war is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
That's the first world war, yes. Yes. And - people used to grow quite a good 
few - vegetables for their own consumption. They were quite - father never had one. I'll tell you what he used to do on Sunday, now - recall it properly, he used to breed greyhounds. Well whippets, not greyhounds, whippets, a small type of - greyhound and
 
- he used to go coursing. And - used to go on Sunday morning - Sunday morning and Sunday afternoon, over the Marshes, Hackney Marshes, and race these whippets. He had three I think, three of four. And - he used to go to have them you know. In fact they us
ed to get preference to us sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 He kept them at the back of the house did he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Kennels at the back - back garden yes, in the - in the kennels. Ordinary - boxes you know made up into houses - kennels they call 'em. But - oh yes, he used to do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 He didn't keep hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, we - I don't remember having chickens. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Or rabbits?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 So they would buy vegetables and fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Buy 'em. They used to go shopping with mother - Saturday morning and - she used to have two
 huge bags, leather bags, shopping bags. Used to get 'em full up with - produce you know, and - I used to carry one she used to carry one, or sometimes me brother go with her you know. And - to get the shopping in. She'd come home with a real load. And - 
'course you could get a joint - joint then for about half a crown, real good joint. Meat was ever so cheap then. And you could take a choice you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 She did get vegetables though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Vegetables. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You don't remember any dried or tinned vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
We used to get - mixed fruit, dried fruit, yes, dried fruit. Have apple rings, pears - peaches, no, not - yes, peaches, nectarines and things like that. Dried fruit. I can't think how much they were a pound but - they were - ever so cheap co
mpared with today. And - ham, used to - used to have a treat sometimes - on Sunday for tea used to have some ham. And - the best ham was two and eight a pound. And - used to go to Home and Colonial for that you see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you get corned beef?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Corned beef, oh yes. Yes, corned - corned beef eightpence a pound I think it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would you have meat most days then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes. Yes. Yes, 'cos used to get a huge joint on Sundays and - used to do all sorts of things to it, you know, during the week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would you have fish instead of meat sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Fish on Fridays usually. Used to buy that - usually from the fried fish shop. Yes. Fish and pastries for after you know. Custard pies and things like that from - from the baker. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would you be able to get rabbits sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would people come round selling those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No, used to go down the market you see, for them. And jellied eels. Jellied eels.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 That was a treat was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 I used to like them. Some - some of t
he family didn't like them, I used to love them. But - now bread - then. Bread used to be sold in half quarten loaves, that was two pounds, to the half quarten loaf. I don't think they used to make quarten loaves, be four pound. But - they used to weigh t
h
em. If they were underweight - they'd make the weight up, and you could choose - what you wished to have, rolls or cakes to make up the weight you see. So they used to weight them with the bread to make up the weight to two pound if they were underweight.
 
Well, as a favourite - cake I liked, we used - they used to call it mince, it was like glorified - glorified bread pudding really, it was lovely though. And I always used to ask for a slice of mince you know to make up the weight. And - I'd eat that befor
e I got home. But - that was what they call make weight. Make weight. Make up weight you see. And then you used to be able to buy a pennyworth of stale cakes. Yes, you go into - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 pastry cooks}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967  - late or Saturday night, you'd take a pillowcase with you, and th
ey practically fill it up with stale cakes for a penny. Oh that used to be a good treat. Yes. There'd the sort of things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Where did your mother cook, there was a kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Kitchen - cooked in - cooked in the kitchen and lived in the kitchen more 
or less, but a big - well, it's all according to the house you're in to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were these houses you moved to virtually the same kind of house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes, same kind of house, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Sometimes there would be a scullery would there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Scullery. A scull
ery where you'd do your washing or - as a - a copper boiler there for boil the clothes in. Or my mother used to boil Christmas puddings in there. She used to do about twelve Christmas puddings at Christmas. Used to boil them in this copper all night they'
d in the copper. She'd boil the clothes on Monday. Christmas puddings on - on Tuesdays, if it happened to be Christmas - time. Yes, they had these small sculleries and old fashioned mangle - wringer we used to call it and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did she have a gas stove though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Toilet out in the garden usually. Gas stove, gas, yes, gas stoves. And then - we used to have a living room with a {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}kitchener{\*\xmlclose}, what they call a {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}kitchener{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} stove in it. Used to do a lot of cooking there, did the meats and - vegetables there. Lovely
 heat the room as well at the same time. That was good that was. Quite big kitchens we had in some places. Kitchen cum living - living room or dining room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Was there any particular house you stayed in for a long time that you can remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, I can't remember staying in any house a long time. I remember \{
ILLEGIBLE\} stayed in for a week. We moved from - North London, Hackney, to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}West End{\*\xmlclose}, Kensington. West End of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}London
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Well - we left home, my sisters and brothers, my young - you know, the yo
ung ones, young - we left home about nine o'clock in the morning - expecting the removal van, which was horse drawn pantechnicon, expecting him to arrive about twelve o'clock. One o'clock. Midday. Father - travel - was traveling with the van. We got to Ke
n
sington to the house - about - twelve o'clock, some - somewhere like that, dinnertime, waiting and waiting and waiting. Do you know how long we waited 'til? Midnight. They arrived at midnight and they were all drunk. The driver - even the horses were drun
k
 I think. And they couldn't do a thing. The - the three men and father. They was all too drink to get a - a chair out. Well - first night wasn't too bad, we just snuggled down on the floor. Next night - the next day we got beds up. Next night we went to b
ed, up all night with bugs. Bugs everywhere. Oh it's terrible, coming out the walls, all bugs you know. It was terrible. And we stuck that for a week. We - we moved to another house just nearby.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Do you think it was your mother or your father who liked moving?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well I don't know, I - I don't really know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You don't remember them saying why they wanted to move?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No. No. Well, one thing he moved to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}West End{\*\xmlclose} for was to be nearer to his work you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did they come back again later?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. Yes, we - we only stayed in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
West End{\*\xmlclose} - two houses when we were there. We stayed there about two years, that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 That was before you were at school though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 I was at school then. Well, just leaving school, I remember - going to
 - Star Lane school. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 In most of the houses would you have to share a bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. Well - the boys. One, two three, three older brothers and - my brother and I, and four - my brother - myself and four older brothers, one next to me, he 
was - about nineteen months older than me and then me older ones. I then - and then we had a lodger as well, one of the brother's friends, he was lodging with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was that for a short time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well, quite a good time. That was really. Yes, that was
 about - one, two - six of us in one bedroom. Yes. Then the girls used to have a bedroom between -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were you top and tail in the bed then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, we - we had separate rooms and good beds, yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were you expected to be in bed by a particular time when you were at school?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Usually, was usually in bed about nine. Yes. Usually in bed about nine.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You just put yourself to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Your mother didn't have anyone to help her in the house then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh no. No, she never had anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would she send the washing out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No, she'd do all the washing. She had a load of washing, she used to take two days usually, Monday and Tuesday. And - I can remember her - can see her now - wringing out the blankets by hand and 
the sheets and as she took them out of the bath water, wringing it like, she'd throw - throw the dry end over her shoulder, give it a wring like that, go like that, wring again and go like that you know, and so that she'd have this - damp sheet or blanket
 
handing on her shoulder. She'd go straight cut into the garden and hang it up on the line. And then you know, she had rheumatism when she was older you know, in her shoulders and - legs. I reckon that caused it you know. But she was tough really. She was 
really tough. Yes, loads of washing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you have a tin bath for a weekly }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 bath night}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes. Yes. That's all. Yes, we didn't have pleasure of a bathroom. Not then. You take it in turns you know, boys one night, girls the next you know. And - then a
fter that we - later on we used to go to public baths. There was the public baths in Hackney. Used to go there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were you expected to help in the house yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes - well as regards household chores, cleaning windows and - cleaning the knive
s and forks and - all these shoes, had to do all the shoes between us, my brother and I used to do - shoes for the older boys - brothers and sisters and mother and father. Used to - you know, quite a lot of shoes to do. And cleaning these knives on the th
e
 old block called knife board. And - it was a long board, like that, with a - a felt stuff on it and you used to - sprinkle brick dust, what they call brick dust onto it. Rub the knives on it until they came up you know. Well, yes, that was a long job. Cl
ean the step. Clean the front door step, you know, got a step, the front door step, with hearthstone, what you call hearthstone. Clean the \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 in the kitchen you know, polish that up with black lead, what you used to call black lead, stove polish, to polish that up. All }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 brass work}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 , we had brass fenders, brass - companion sets, and you had to clean them up, make them look nice and bright. Yes, we were never idle.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were the older ones expected to look after the younger ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes, they told us what to do - as well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would they sometimes take you out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Sometimes. Not very often, but - we used to look forward to father taking us out on bank Holidays. Yes. He usually - usually used to take us to - Hampstead - Hampstead Heath, there us
ed to be big fairs there you know, roundabouts, swings, all that. Coconut shie. But - there was always fight. You always expect a fight and usually used to get it. Big - people used to get drunk. It was quite common thing to see people drunk in the street
,
 any time. Any time of the week. But at Hampstead - there used to be a free for all, perhaps - there'd be an argument you know, men would take their belts off, splay one another with their belts, the dust would fly up. Then the women would join in. They h
a
t - they take their hat pins out, start - digging one another with hat pins. Used to be terrible. You couldn't see them for dust hardly, dust was flying. And do you know, that used to happen nearly every time. But we all - we used to go just the same. And
 then - remember 'em - on August Bank Holiday Monday 1914 my father took us to Highgate to Queens Woods, Highgate, and on the - previous midnight - so - Sunday midnight war was declared on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Germany{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And there was an edition of the paper came out while we wer
e - in the park as the new - newspaper come around, all the latest news you know, war declared and I can remember father reading it and he said to my mother, old woman, and he used to say, it started and, he said, we don't know when it will end. He said, 
it'll be four years at least. And it was four years. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did he read you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 He wouldn't help put you to bed or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What about helping with anything in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh no, he was
 the boss and that was it you know and - everybody was at his back and call. You see he used to get drunk sometimes. And when he got drunk he was nasty with it, he wasn't funny you know. And I remember my mother telling me a story about when they had thei
r
 first child, my oldest brother - father came home drunk one night, they'd only got that one child, and - Bill, the oldest brother, he was about four or five at the time, father came home absolutely drunk and he swept everything off the mantelpiece. He we
n
t like that, all the - ornaments all smashed, except one. Well brother Bill, he goes into father's workshop - gets his hammer, brings his hammer out said, dad - daddy, you missed that one. And he gave him the hammer so that he could smash the last ornamen
t on the ma}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
tel, and she said, you know, I've never seen your dad sober up so quickly before. It absolutely sobered him up and he was absolutely ashamed of himself. He hung his head and walked out the room. But - a - a wonderful story that, a true one. Dadd
y, he said, you missed one, like that. And he gave him his hammer to finish it off. It sounds a - a made up story but it's true. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 He'd go out to drink then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes, get - get with his pals and - he'd get drunk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 How often a week would he usually go out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh not - not very often. He - not very often used to come - come home like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 How often would he go out to a pub?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - two or three nights a week. Two or three nights and usually a weekend. Sunday, you know, come home late for dinner. I still do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 How wouldn't light a fire for instance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh no. Oh no. Oh no. No, he wouldn't -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What about painting when it was needed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
I never remember him - painting. Painted the house at all. Don't ever remember painting any - any house. Or any decorating either come to that. He'd just - sooner move house than decorate or paint it. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 So the one thing he really would do was mend the shoes for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. He'd do - mend - mend your shoes, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would your mother make the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
I can't remember her making - any - can't remember doing - seeing her doing any needlework. Darning and things like that but - not making anything. Pass - we used to pass them down, used to - neighbours us
ed to give - you know - exchange and all that, we used to do that and pass them down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 So they were mainly secondhand clothes?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. Yes. Yes. You always had your Sunday best you know, you always had that. Once a week put your Sunday best on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did she make any medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. No, the only medicines we had - was - licorice - licorice - licorice powder. And - horrible stuff, I don't know if you've ever had it, but - she used to say, hold your nose. We used to hold our nose 'cos you could
 smell it as well, we used to put the teaspoonful down or whatever the dose was, and then - have another teaspoonful with a - a - jam in it, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 If you had a birthday would that be any different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No, never - celebrat
ed in any way. Just - had a present of some kind but - but didn't have a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 tea party}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967  or party or - like you know, usually do now, children invite their pals in. Never did that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was there anyone in the family who played a musical instrument?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. Oh
 yes there was, brother Jim, he - he used to. He used to play a banjo. But - sister tried to learn a either but she couldn't get on with it. My other brother nearest to me used to play the piano by ear, you know, but - now I come to think of it it was pre
tty awful really, you - I used to think it was all right then, but - I never had a chance - I'd liked to have done but I couldn't afford lessons.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You had a piano in the house did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes, same piano, well we didn't have that until - about - '18 
I think, after '18. After the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Not when your father was alive?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No, not when he was alive, no. No, but brother used to play a banjo in - at -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would you all sing together then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes, we'd have a sing-song, oh yes, all have a good 
sing-song together, yes. And father used to like singing sort of Irish songs you know. Yes. Farmer O'Flynn and Simon the Cellarman and that sort of thing you know, Killarney and - he used to like for me to sing as well, he'd always ask me to sing at a par
t
y, because I used to have a very musical voice you know and - at school I was commended you know and - for singing. They always get me - to get up and sing something. That's a real - good time at Christmas, there's usually at Christmas time. We never used
 to have any parties - apart from Christmas. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were there many books in the house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No, there were very few books really. I - I - I can't ever remember seeing anybody - reading - a book, a good book you know. Well we didn't have them. I - I got
 rather fond of reading later on you know, after - 1918. Used to read quite a lot of books, usually - mostly novels. Since then I got more interested in biographies and autobiographies, that's what I liked. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 But you don't remember your mother and father reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - mother was illiterate. Yes. Couldn't read or write. Father - wasn't very good - the - he - he'd be quite good at dictating, he did - he - he wouldn't write but he - dictate it and my sisters would usually write his letters. See
, he was all right dictating, he wasn't very good handwriting. But mother was - couldn't read or write. But she could do mental arithmetic. She was very good really on reckoning up things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did he take a newspaper then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes, always took a newspaper, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Do you know what it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well it was called then the Daily Chronicle, which is now the Daily Mail. It became the New Chronicle, after dad had gone it became the News Chronicle, then that - then it amalgamated with Daily Mail, it's al
l one paper. And News of the World Sundays. Sunday I used to devour the News of the World on Sunday. Oh what other paper was it used to have as well? Reynolds. Reynolds. But we dare not look at it. If he saw us pick up - you mustn't read that, you know. T
hat was after we was about fifteen or sixteen he wouldn't let us read it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Why do you think that was then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well - filthy some of it was. Plenty of filth in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you find him an easy man to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well - I never got on with my father, 
myself. I - really I hated my father. I say it, I know he's dead and I still say it. I don't - I don't know why it was but - when he - he was so strict you know, if he gave us a good hiding he - he used to lay it on too - too bad. And my mother stopped hi
m
 one day, beating us, 'cos she - she said we'd been bad, done something bad and - she said chastise them you know. But he laid it on so thick - she - intervened. And he said, never ask me to chastise them again, he said. I thought, oh, that's good. So - d
idn't make any difference really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 He would quite often punish you then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Very short tempered, yes. Very short tempered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would he quite often punish you like that though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well we were quite often - you know - bit naughty. Didn't very of
ten get away with it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 She wouldn't normally punish you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh no, she - she wouldn't punish you. She'd - frighten you, she say, I'll tell your dad. I'll tell your father. Never used to say dad or mum, always father and mother. I'll tell your father
, see. But - she wouldn't always. But - sometimes when we were extra naughty - she would. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 So you felt rather closer to her then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes. Oh yes, closer to her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 She was easy to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. Well I s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 uppose she used to - favouritism}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
 me a bit you know because - you know I'd been so delicate and that and - very delicate I suppose she used to look after me more really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 If you were worried about something you could talk to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Confined. Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 How would you say that your parents expected you to behave towards them?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well respect you know and - do as you were told - obey. Obey them. Well we used to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Did they bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in certain ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No. No. No, no
t - not - in the family, not - no, not respecting one another or loving one another, no, never laid out - down any hard and fast rules about that, but always - be respectful to people outside the family and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 If another child hit you did they say you should hit back or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes, they'd say, well - well you know what to do, hit him back. They never used to take sides. There was never any trouble - with - neighbours through - through children, not - not through our family. I don't think that
 was at all. I - can't remember any - rows between neighbours. Not really. 'Cos - more or less all on same level you know. Same problems and they shared them. They did used to share - real neighbourliness. We used to have Jews next door to us one house we
 lived. And they were ever so good to us, so - they were - they were better off than we were really. They were ever so good to us.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 When you say they were good to you you mean they would lend things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Give you things you know, yes. Yes. And - late
r on - when we - during the war and after the war, we moved to - Hackney, a place called {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Devonshire Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, well that's right next to - a synagogue. Well - we - my brother and I, we used to go into that synagogue and - and help - to clear up, because the car
etaker, he lodged with us you see, him and his family, they had two - two rooms I think it was or three rooms, upstairs, a fairly big house. And - we used to go in and help him. Well we got to know the Rabbi and other people and - they were ever so good, 
a
nd - they used to give us things and give us money as well and that. And - on their special feast days, the Feast of Passover and that - we used to go into their houses and do chores for them because they weren't allowed to do anything. And - we used to e
ven - have to pull lavatory chain for them after they'd been to the toilet. They weren't allowed to do that. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 That was when you were quite young you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes, I suppose I was in - in me - teens then, about fourteen, fifteen. Fifteen. Before
 that I think it was. Yes. What am I thinking about, thirteen. And - used to - light the gas for them and - lighting their gas stoves and the gas light and that. They wouldn't do anything like that, they were so - devout religion. Wouldn't - wouldn't - do
 a thing you know on those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
What sort of people do you think that your parents hoped that you would grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - I don't think they had - any ideas really of the prospects. They just thought of a trade you know. Now - my brother, one next to me, he wasn't in the shoe trade, he was apprenticed to carpentry and joinery, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 shop fitting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
. He was the only one in the family who - who had a opportunity. I didn't get the opportunity 'cos father died - before, I wanted to go into sign writing, s
ee, but I never had a chance, I went into this warehouse. They couldn't afford to - pay for apprenticeship. But - I don't think they had - they had any ambitions for their children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What did they think was really important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Money. For - 
form - I mean, money - not excess of money but - money to keep - family going, keep body and soul together. That's - that's what I think. Sure - sure they thought that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What was their attitude to swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh well - I - very much against it.
 I don't think I've heard - I have heard them swear. Mother or father. No. Sure - sure I didn't. Used to use a few slang words you know, like arse and things like that you know, oh used to say that, silly arse and things like that you know but - I - I kno
w - never heard them used any - bad words. They - they were against it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 That would be one sign of the religion maybe?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well I don't know. If it was or - or - or not but - naturally - 'cos some people naturally don't like it do they. Like - a part
y I was at on - Saturday night - my wife's cousin - she met - another cousin, she hadn't seen her for years, she said, well I - well I'm - well I'm - I'm buggered, like that, you know, and it - hit me coming from her, who'd expected her to say that. Don't
 
know why she said it but I'd never dream of - you know, it really - and so did my wife. She said - when we came home, she said, fancy Kitty saying that. I said, oh did you notice it? She said, oh yes. She said, I wonder why. I said, no. I said, just lost 
for a word and she must use that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 As a child were you allowed to join in when grown ups were talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh no. Speak when you've spoken to. That was - that was the rule. That was the golden rule really. Speak when you're spoken to. Oh yes, used to be none of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Would you say that, even though you didn't like your father, he was an influential in the way that you grew up as your mother was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well I think they share it you know, really with mother and father, as regards - manners and - good manners and that. But we were taught - also at school, good manners. And - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What sort of way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Like - not to walk in front of a lady was one. And - I remember that, that particular teacher was telling us about being good manners and t
hat. They say if you have to - if you're - forced to walk in front of a lady - you must turn to her - or - or a gentleman - and say, I beg your pardon. See? So I though, oh that's good, so - on the way home from school I always used to pass a big drapers 
a
nd there was always ladies looking in the window you know. I thought, oh here's my chance, you know. 'Cos I walked right between the ladies - round ladies and - and the window and say, oh pardon me, pardon me, pardon me. I always think of it now, I mean i
t's funny really. I said, oh pardon me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did they correct the childrens ways of speaking as well at the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes. Oh yes. Yes. And - we had big classes then. Yes. Seventy in a class. And - the - bottom of the class was the bottom of the class, 
if you was at the bottom of the class you were in the front row. If you were in the top class you're in top row you see, 'cos these seats used to go up on an angle. Well I was always down there when I was at school, I was always down the bottom. But there
 
used to be - over seventy in some classes and - they grumble now don't they if they've got thirty or forty. But I admit that they couldn't teach to 'em properly, so - having so many children. You see, I was absolutely - shunned really, 'cos - I was so bac
kward - I - they passed me as hopeless. Well today, I would go to a school for retarded children wouldn't I. You see. Get a chance now. But it never had that then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 How old were you when you started school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 About - eight. Eight. And then - t
hen I was off again and - until I was fourteen. Yes I - in - in and out of hospital. Convalescing and - in and out of - out - out patient as well you know for - ages - years, really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 So you'd be months in hospital at a time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. Yes. Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were you rather miserable when you were in hospital or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. No, I wasn't miserable no. And - I was in - in - one hospital in the Hackney Road, Queens Hospital for children and Hackney Road and - in - on - if it was a fine day used to put 
you out on the balcony, I used to like that. And - I - every now and again you'd see a fight, a street fight, from the balcony. Women and men. Just like I described at Hampstead Heath. And I remember one - had a turning right opposite where my bed was and
 
I saw a fight start up there with some women. And - the hat pins were going you know and they're scratching one another - all blood stream - and - they're having a running fight. And they're coming towards the hospital to Hackney Road, and they went right
 
across there, and when they got to the other side, down to Goldsmith Road, men joined in fighting. So it's men and women and they was having a running battle right from one street right across the High Road to the next street and just - disappeared out of
 sight. But it was quite common to see women like that. See them have a row in a factory, perhaps they'd row behind the factory or - some argument. Well when they came out of work they'd have - used to fight it out. Terrible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were there similar sort of fights at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes, there were always fights between the boys at school. I remember one. Now - during the war years there was a very great shortage of teachers. And we were - were without teachers. The headmaster just used to h
ave to come in and give us some lessons to do and then leave us to it and come back and see how we got on. Well - we - eventually we got a lady teacher. And I used to play her up. I was terrible really. You know, I - I realize how bad I was really. Used t
o
 cheek her and - well there's one boy and - he - he - determined to - give me a good hiding for it see. His name was Charlie Bean. And - so he go me in the playground, it was on a winter's day, and it was all slides over the playground where the boys had 
b
een making slides on the snow - on the ice. And he said - Mulligan, he said - he said, I - he said, you've been upsetting our teacher, he said. I said, yes, why, what of it? You know, like that. Well you shouldn't do it, he said, I'm going to give you a g
o
od hiding. So I says, all right, come and try it. Try to do it you see. So we - we started fighting. Well - eventually he - he got me onto this slide. And every time - I lunged out at him I slipped on the slide. I kept going down on me backside and gettin
g
 up and he was knocking me down again. He didn't give me a chance to get up. And he gave me a jolly good hiding. You know, it done me good. But do you know - some years after that I met him. We were in our - trenches then, and I said to him, do you rememb
e
r Charlie when you got me on that slide, I said and gave me a jolly good - yes, he said, I remember it, he said, I was just going to ask you if you remembered it. He was champion then you know of course. Made - made a difference, I was all right after tha
t
. But we were always - always fights in the playground. In fact - there was one teacher there, he was rather sporty - sporty teacher, if he used to see a fight when you go out in the playground he used to come and referee it. He - he wouldn't stop you. An
o
ther teacher would stop you, take your names and say, come and see me, and you get - get the stick. Well, talking about - get - getting the stick - our headmaster, he was an absolute sadist, he must have been, because if you were late for school you had t
o
 go straight in to the hall and wait for the headmaster to come. Well - usually there was eighteen, twenty, perhaps thirty boys lined up in the hall, all late. And if you got a note from your parents or not, you'd get two handers, get the stick, two hands
 
like that, and he used to give it to you stiff. And that's the way he used to start his day. By caning boys. We used to think how terrible he was. Hall his name was, I - can remember him, I never forget him. And I used to thin-to myself, 'cos I - I've had
 several - handers from him, and I used to think to myself, oh fancy starting the day like that. You know, it's bad enough for us but it must be - awful way to start the day, cane - punishing boys. But he used to love it. So that shows you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you like any of the teachers at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes, some of them were loves, some of them - some of them didn't like. Some of them were - really nasty you know, and - others were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Can you tell me about one you liked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes, there was one named - Mr B
arrow and that - that's the one who used to referee a fight. When I was in his class - we had - he bought an object for us to paint and it was a Meresham Pipe. Do you know - know what Meresham Pipe is? And ordinary smokers pipe but - a very large curve on
 
it and a very large bowl. Yellow in colour. Meresham wood I believe it's made of. And - he said, boy who paints it best - he said, I'll allow him to have a smoke of it. So I did it best. So he said, would you like a smoke? I said, yes please sir. Are you 
s
ure? Yes please sir. So he says, all right. So he fills it up. He said, all right, have a good draw. And I had a good draw at it. Oh - felt awful, I felt shocking. A long while after I felt sick, but he was laughing, all the boys were laughing. And then -
 
I used to go down to his house at Chingford, he had a nice bungalow at Chingford and - a lovely peach trees in his garden, used to go down there and help him with the garden. He usually used to say, take these home to your mother. He used to give me about
 half a dozen lovely peaches you know, great big ones like - he was nice.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Do you think he sort of singled you out really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. No, he - he was nice to - I wasn't the only one that used to go down - to his house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 But they did treat children differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes. Yes. But he was the only one that treated me - you know - was sorry for me I think really 'cause I - I was so backward. Another teacher - Nelson his name and he - he'd only got one eye incidentally, he had really, he was terrible. He
 was - he took standard four, this was the - middle standard and the - hardest standard there was. And - my brother was in his class once, well he was smart, and - and I was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 dunce}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 . And - I got a sum wrong one day. And - he called me out in front of the c
lass, he said, I can't understand you, he said, you're not a bit like your brother, your brother's smart and you're a dunce, he said, you can't do sums. So I said, well I'm sorry sir, I can't help it, I've had a lot of illness. So he turned to the boys an
d
 said, oh hear what he said, he's ill, he said, he's ill, he's been ill? Oh like that, you know, absolutely - made me feel like a worm. So - he said, do it - on the blackboard, he said. - So I did it on the blackboard and I got it right. I couldn't - I do
n
't know why. So he said, there you are. Made it worse for me. You see, there you are, you can do it, you must be absolutely lazy. He said, you did it with the ease of an expert. He said, and - and yet you couldn't do it just now. You know. I didn't know w
hy I got it right, really I couldn't - not to this day. But he used to make me feel awful. And - and the difference you know in the two teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was it all boys at these schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 All boys - yes, all boys - like that school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were they mostly from similar homes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. Yes. Yes. Most of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was one of those schools in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
West End{\*\xmlclose}?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 One of them, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Star Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, yes. Yes. I don't remember much of the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}West End{\*\xmlclose} one - I - I - couldn't have gone there much. I know - oh yes. Star Lane, sc
hool - that was in Kensington. I wasn't there very long, we were only in Kensington for two years. And I didn't get much schooling out of that. But - we used to - there used to be another school next to it, what they called a special school, and that - th
a
t was for - children who were really, you know - mental. And I was very often - the teacher told me he'd send me there you know, if I couldn't improve. It was funny. And - and then the one in Hackney and - that was bigger school and - and nearly all boys,
 
a very big school and - but used to be a man - vending honeycomb. Have you ever seen honeycomb? It's - like the - comb of a - a hive, see, not - not - not - not the actual cells, the outside - solid, and it's sugary. And he used to sell this honeycomb fro
m
 a barrow for a ha'penny or farthing - ha'penny - ha'penny a lump. It was great big lump like that. Used to stick it in newspaper, no plain paper, stick it in newspaper, and we used to enjoy that. But - the trouble was, used to - buy it just before we wen
t
 into school, didn't know what to do with it when we got in school you see. Our fingers were sticky. And we used to stick it under the desk. If it was a hot day it started running. But our papers - used to get shocking, used to get all sticky and give thi
s
 - comb started sugar you know and syrup and that and used to get in trouble, we were - forbidden to take it into school eventually. Rather funny. And they used to sell - all sorts of things outside - toffee apples. Farthing a toffee apple. Marvellous rea
lly. And - this - the school, Morning Lane, I'm talking about now, is the school I was at during the war, during the first war, and there was a shortage of teachers.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Those are board schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes, ordinary - ordinary L.C.C. - L.C. - London County Council board school.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Do you remember any really poor children at these schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes, there was - some really - really ragged children you know, they used to wear plimsolls in the winter, black plimsolls, hadn't got shoes. But - you didn't see so much poverty there, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}North London{\*\xmlclose}
, as you did in South East London. I used to go over to South East London, I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 courting}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967  a girl over there when I was about - seventeen or eighteen. And - we used to go round a place called Nunhead, Peckham way, and i
t was really - oh it was heartbreaking there. I used to see children - practically naked sitting out on the kerbs and - just got a shirt on, and filthy. Absolutely filthy. Boys with just a shirt on, girls with just a - a slip, you know, and mothers and fa
thers in their doorways probably - sitting out in - father was half drunk and - some of the mothers as well. Really pitiful but - you didn't see - see it as bad as that in North London.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would these much poorer children at the school be left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. Oh no, they wouldn't be left out of things at all. And - they used to have - special tickets - soup kitchens then, they used to give children food - dinner coupons then. If they couldn't afford dinner used to have this coupon, used to go into
 a - a coffee shop and had a - what they called coffee shop. Have you ever seen a coffee shop? They're - no, well - got benches - benches and they're back to back and - it's all quite rough woodwork you know and - you really get a good meal in a coffee sh
o
p and cheap you know and - if you were ordering a - a meat pudding you'd ask for a baby's head and things like that and you - ordering rippers you'd say jack the rippers, you know. Things like that. Slang - but - used to get a jolly good meal there for ei
g
htpence, get a good dinner for eightpence. And after, prunes and custard you know, rhubarb and custard, like that. And - get a cup of coffee and - and - go in the morning and get a cup of coffee or a cup of cocoa for - for tuppence I think it was, penny o
r tuppence. Great big cup like that, thick cup, heavy you - know but - and bread and dripping, I used to love bread and dripping there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 That was by the time you were working though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. That - that was - that was a little later on. But the chil
dren used to go into these places to get their sup, their - their dinners, with these - dinner tickets. And I think - the Daily Mirror, used to issue them also. They had a scheme - a soup coupons. And - you buy a Daily Mirror and you get a coupon in it an
d you can send it to a certain address and they just distribute them to poor children. A good scheme really. 'Course - it's different now isn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were you ever taken out visiting relations as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. Yes. Aunts and uncles and - a few you 
now and - or cousins usually you know. My - my mother - she had one sister. She lived over at Bermondsey, used to go and visit her. But I'd no relations of me father's. Oh yes there was - 'course there was. There was his - his brother's wife, Aunt Harriet
. She had children. Used to visit them. But - never any - only pay flying visits you know, don't think we ever stayed any - length of time. 'Cos you just - just couldn't afford to entertain people really. Didn't like - you know, impose on them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You say people used to drop into the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes, they used to into - ours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What about your dropping into other peoples houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You didn't do that so much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Your father wouldn't go and drop in on somebody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, not 
- well not - not with the family you know. Might drop in - one or two of his - pals you know - and that but - not very often. If he went out anywhere he used to go out in - as part of the family - never the whole family together. No. 'Cos the - the }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 disparity}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
 in the ages you see. One had their own amusements you see so - but the younger children, we used to go - mum and dad if we did go out anywhere. To see Aunt - Aunt Harriet or - cousins you know, married cousin. But -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You were talking about these ga
mes you played as children, would your mother and father join in with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No, used to - usually play on our own. Just the children's games. Mother was usually busy - in the kitchen, you know, it's always in the kitchen or in the scullery. But - fath
er'd be - playing a game of cards or something like that you know. With some of his pals come in or with the older boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Would you say that your mother and father had separate friends or did they share the same friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, they - shared. Shared
 the same friends. My father had a particular friends who was a Jew. And he's an Irishman. And - usually he had - Irish and Jews don't get on together don't you. But this man, his name was Mr Levi, and - he was - a real - nice man and he - he was fairly w
e
ll off, he was a tailor, he - and he lived in Bethnal Green, Petticoat Lane. And - he used to - be very fond of my younger sister. He was always buying her presents. And al - and always leave her some money you know after he left the - always leave money 
to - put a pound in - you know before he - before he left, he'd always leave a few bob and really got on well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You said you mostly had secondhand clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you ever buy those at jumble sales or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, they were usually g
iven you by other people. I - in fact I - I don't remember jumble sales, not in those days. Can't remember them, no. Not in my younger days, they - came a bit later on you know. But not in - not when I was a child. I don't remember anything - about jumble
 sales at all. They were mostly given.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Who would give them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Neighbours and - or they'd exchange you see, things like that you see. 'Course being a - rather big family you couldn't - lot of them were handed down you see. When - brother - -when the
y got too small for big brother you'd have them and - things like that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you take any sort of family magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
All I can remember is - magazine my sisters used to take and the Christian Herald. That's - the only one I can remember comin
g in - when I was a child. But - can't remember any other - special magazine coming in, just the newspaper as a rule. Seven days a week you know. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
You told me about the Bank Holiday outings with your mother and father, were there any times when you went out just with your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No, usually - no, mother and father - always with mother and father. YES. Yes. No doubt it was an outing for her as well as us you know, 'cos she didn't get out much only probably on Bank Holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 She would never go out in the evenings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No, I've never known her - known her to be out. Never known - I've never known to leave us on our own. Well, I'll tell you - no, that's wrong there 'cos I remember once left on our own. That's when we lived in Clapton, Nor
th London. And - I had an accident while they were out, I cut me face there. Jumped through a - a glass panel in the door. That's a - a funny thing really. And - we were on our own, there was just - my brother and my younger sister, three of us, and - we 
l
ived in a shop you see, we - me father had a shop and - there's a basement attached to this house and you used to go through the shop, down the stairs to the basement then you were in the house and this particular night when - we were left on our own - we
 
were there's a door at the foot of the stairs, these stairs, with a glass panel in it you see. Well - we kept the door open by putting a - a cushion against it and we were jumping off the stairs into the basement living room see. And - seeing who could ju
m
p the farthest, going up as many stairs you could and see who jumped the farthest you see. Well - we'd done several jumps or dives we called them and - I was just about to do my dive you know - from about the tenth stair and - I was half - I was in the ai
r
 and my brother took the cushion away from the door and the wind caught it somehow and it slammed to and we met and I went right through the door. Cut my face like that now. We didn't know what to do, we were panic stricken. Just then my elder brother cam
e
 home. He rushed me off to the German hospital in Hackney, there's a hospital - there's a German hospital. And - anyway - the doctor put - just five stitches in it you know. And he gave me half a crown, which was a lot of money then. And he said, that's f
or being a brave fellow, 'cos I never whispered. Got half a crown. Yes. That's the only time I can remember - well the first time I can remember being left alone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did your father often have a shop then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, you see, the only shop he ever had. Tha
t's from about 1909 to 1911. And we were only there two years and - there was father - and two brothers had it, and they used to make shoes as well to order, see, on the premises, and also used to buy in - for resale. And - the older brother of the two - 
h
e had promised not to get married - until - the business was going all right. Well eventually he did get married. Before the stipulated time, he wanted to get married, he was anxious to get married, that caused a bit of a upheaval and a bit of a row. And 
- he left and he got married you see. Yes, and - started on his own, making outdoors you know, making shoes outdoors. And - the business seemed to - go down after that. And so father moved to the West End. To the West End of London.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 In 1911 he closed the shop then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would it be in the autumn or the summer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No, it's in the summer. 'Cos that was the time when I was telling you about when we moved to Fulham, to the West End, and when they arrived at about midnight, father and the remo
val men, arrived at midnight and I - I know it was summer. Because the bugs were active.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 So they were selling their own shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were there other people employed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No. No. Well - they - they didn't have a very big cliente
le you know to - just ladies in the vicinity and - father used to make them to measure for them. But most of it was bought in - shoes, boots and shoes. That could have been - prosperous business I should think, you know, if brother hadn't moved out.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Who served in the shop then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Father usually, father and - father and the older brother. But usually father used to serve in the shop. And - he used to have - big - what they call butts of leather and he used to buy leather in a butt, that was a whole 
- skin of an animal. Minus it's legs and that, but it - it's like the whole skin. And they - these butts used to stand about - six or seven feet high and they were about four or five feet across. The whole animal. Never saw - I never saw - I've never seen
 'em since. No. Now, you buy them in bins, what they call a bin. It's usually the back. And the sides. It was marvellous - it was marvellous leather as well then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 All made to measure the shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 All made to measure, yes. Yes. And - we - as childre
n, we used to - deliver - we used to do repairs as well, dad did, and we used to deliver them to the customers you see. Mostly round - the neighbourhood. Nearly all just local. And - there was some very very - wealthy people in that area. A place called S
tamford Hill, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}North London{\*\xmlclose}. And very big houses. Very wealthy people. And - quite nice you know. Used to - give us something for ourselves nearly every time we took the shoes home. Spending money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Could you tell me anything more about those people, wha
t sort of jobs do you think the had and so on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well, something in the city I expect the - the head of the house was you know but - I think some of them were retired people. But - they were quite - what we used to call gentle - gentry then you know, upper class. Upper class - neighbourhood. Really.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would they drive around in carriages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes. Yes. Yes. Some of 'em had a car. Old fashioned car you know. Old fashioned car with brass lamps on it and all that. But they did have carriages.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were you brought up to treat them with special respect?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. Yes. Oh yes. You always - always - father used to say, mind your p's and q's. When you go there. Else you'll hear about it, oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Where would you draw the line for the people t
hat you would call sir at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well we never drew a line. Never drew a line, it was always sir or madam. Always. Anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Anybody who was a customer you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. Sir or madam.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 But outside the shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Outside as well. Fathe
r always taught us - that. Yes. Yes. He used to do the same, we used to follow him you see. But we always taught us - were taught us to - address our elders in the proper manner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 So that would be anybody who was grown up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Anybody that was grown up then. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
What about these rather poorer families, you were among the more prosperous working class weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
There - there we were, it was only for a couple of years, but - mostly we're - amount people of our own class. And - we use
d to call them by christian names you know, except - and - an adult we'd call mister or miss or missus, mister and missus or miss you see. We never called our parents mum or dad or pop or anything like that. Mother and father, always mother and father.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would you call another grown up men in the working class sir or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - it's according - it was according to - his seniority you see, if you was on a level with him - just call him by his christian name, perhaps he got to be called by his chris
tian name. But you - you wouldn't address him - sir, but you'd address him as mister and then probably by his christian name - later on when you got to know him or - or if he addressed you by your christian name. Now - I mean - I took liberty of addressin
g
 you as Paul didn't I, you see, well - I - it's only recently I - I've got like that. That sort of thing 'cos I think it's - more friendly. It's a christian name and - greet you as a christian. And - but there's - there's some people even now I - I wouldn
'
t address by their christian name, I don't know why, there's two - two - of our members there and - call Mr Moss and Mr Bowman, I never call them by their christian name and he - he'd do the same to me, he'd call me by my surname. But occasionally you kno
w
, if you're - doing a job together, working together you - use the christian names. But - it's strange really. I was picked up on that the other day - a young lady, she - takes the Sunday school, the babies in Sunday school, and - I always call her Mrs Pa
rr because - her name is Mrs Parr. She - she picked me up the other day, she said, June please. June please. And - I still call her Mrs Parr. Strange isn't it. Yes. Yes. Sunday I called her Mrs Parr - June then. That's better. Charles.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 How were you brought up to think of the poorer people in the working classes?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - brought up to - what, poorer than ourselves? Poor than ourselves, well brought up to sympathise with them and try to help them, do what you could for them, for your neighbours if -
 they're a bit worse off than yourself, I mean we weren't - we weren't well off but we were - comfortable. But there were many who were - were poorer. And - I know my - my sisters - my oldest sisters - at Christmastime, they would always go down to the ma
r
ket in Chatworth Road in Hackney, always go down to the market with - little parcels and a little silver threepenny bit, an orange or an apple, perhaps both and - a little something for a boy or for a girl and a little - they'd go down the market look at 
t
he kiddies all round the stalls looking at things on the stalls Christmastime, toys, then go up and say, this is for you. And give 'em a little parcel for themselves and - they thought that was - a good thing to do, which it was I think you know, it showe
d
 - sympathy. 'Cos they were better off - they were better off then them. But the children, they did used to appreciate it, well I - I carried on doing that in me later - later life when I - when I met my present wife, I said - told her what me sisters use
d to do you see. So she said, do you know, she said, we do that. My - Edie and I, that's her sister, she said, we do that. So she said, we can do it together. So we used to go down to the market in Walthamstow. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}St James Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Called {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Hoe Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}St James Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, that's a bit off of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Hoe Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and - you'd be surprised at the joy on the kids face you know. Little tiny present like that. And it comes so unexpectedly. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you feel that some of these poor families were very rough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes. Yes. O
h yes, we used to - say they were rough you know but - they'd still got the same - make up as us really you know although it was the conditions that made 'em rough I think. And - it was usually due to the parents that the children were rough. The parents 
w
ere rough and children were rough. They used to be very rough some of them - Well, when I was telling you about women and men fighting in the streets, I mean, what else do you expect the family to do. See. They were the sort you used to have at school use
d to - always challenge to fight or something like that, or rough you up, you know. Like these gangs you get now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 There were gangs in the school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. Oh yes. Oh yes, they used to go by different names. Some of them used to wear black caps, black cap gang and check cap gang. And - they used to regard them school age up to about sixteen or seventeen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did they wear these different kinds of clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Caps - just caps you see. A black cap or a checked cap. My brother was - he - he j
oined - he - he - got in friendly with a - very rough sort of chap. This was - just after he went out to work. And this chap lived - off the City somewhere, Stepney way and he was rather rough and - and he belonged to this gang, the checked cap gang you s
e
e. My brother belonged to it as well, he used to come home with this check cap on, pulled down over one eye you know. My mother said, what are you wearing? You know. My check cap, he said, he said, I belong to the gang. She said, you're not going to belon
g
 to any gang, you know. And - they went away together on a holiday, they went to Eastbourne. And they nearly got run in - there, people were shunning them you knew and - I suppose they'd heard about them in London and - like these - these - what - ton up 
b
oys you know. Hells Angels. I mean, it does repeat itself over and over again, I mean, started it in my childhood days and it's still carrying on now. Different gangs. It's still - it's still the same. I expect when Hell's Angels go something'll take the 
place - take their place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
But in that time do you think the different between the rough and the respectable was more important between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well there was a distinction between craftsmen and labourers. They thought they were v
ery - very low on the social scale, labourers you know. But a craftsman was something, he got some status but - labourer hadn't really. And - well - I think it's the same now really. Although there's not so many craftsmen in existence now. Real craftsmen.
 'Cos everything's done mass production, such a line, that you - that you can't say there's real craftsmen in some cases you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Did you feel that was a more important distinction really than between rough and respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No I don't think so. 
No, don't think that was more important, no. No, not really. It's hard to describe really, your feelings, how you felt. For those people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You could think of a labourer as being respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh you could think of being respectable but not - no s
tatus as yourself you know. I mean, you - you'd be friendly with him and - perhaps very friendly, but - I think - they - they used to feel the same really, they felt they were a bit inferior because they hadn't got a craft - follow. It was good to have a 
craft really. Because it stood you in good stead. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Do you think your mother had the same sort of attitude to this kind of question as your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well I think - it wasn't her own attitude, it was an attitude - that she had - inherited from h
im really 'cos he was boss, what he said was right you see. Now - for one thing - I wanted to join a Boy Scouts, Scout movement. He wouldn't - wouldn't - hear of it you know. He used to hate - he used to say they were a military organisation, the Scouts. 
A
nd - there's a chap, he lived in our road and he was a Scoutmaster, his name was Buckmaster and - he asked me to join and I said, well I'll ask my dad. So he said, oh he won't object. I said, I - I think he will. So anyway I asked him. No, you're not goin
g to join any Scouts, he said, you're not going to be brought up to kill people. I said, it's not, I said, no, I said, you don't carry a gun, I said, you carry a ple}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 . Never mind, he said, you get instruction. So he said, you let - you wait until I see that
 - that Scoutmaster, I - I shall tell him what I think of him. And that. So I - I was frightened, I told the Scoutmaster what he said. I said, he won't let me join. He was dead against - Scout movement. And - what he said you know you had to adhere to. Yo
u couldn't do anything about it. Dare not - go against his orders.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yet you said he went to the Arsenal during the war for patriotic reasons?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes. Well - I don't know - did I say for patriotic reasons. Did I mention? Yes. Well, partly I mean - but
 mostly to get the money. Pocket money really, more money. Like - during - during that war, there's a lot of people - went into munitions to get the money. Boys used to say to me - boys I knew from school, fancy sticking that job in a warehouse. - Why don
'
t you come with me railway - down the munitions factory, earn - so many pounds a week, about ten pound a week, something like that, and I was getting about thirty bob you know, then. Oh no, I said, there's no future in it. No future in it. The war's not g
oing to last forever. No, that doesn't matter, you get the money, have a good time. I think that was partly the reason he went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
You mentioned your brother had this holiday, did you go away for holidays as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 As a child - we went away, my br
other and I - to a holiday home, once we went away. Passmore Edwards Holiday Home, Clacton-on-Sea, it belongs to the University now don't it, of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}
. Part of it. And - it was - there was - while we were there there was a ship which sank just off of Clact
on, about two miles off the - Express of Ireland I think it was called. And - all hands were lost, and we could see from the windows of the dormitories the rockets, distress rockets going up. It happened at night time. It was ever so thrilling. And - I've
 
got a card somewhere which we sent to my mother, telling her we were having a lovely time. But we weren't really. No. 'Cos - we did it - at times but - in - outside the home we had a nice time but inside the home - we didn't have a very nice time at all. 
T
he food wasn't good and - the matron was very very very strict. And she used to spank you for anything you know. Any trifling little thing. I - I remember one night, all the boys were - big dormitory, all the boys were having a pillow fight. We were all s
l
inging our pillows, fighting you know, and matron came in. Oh she went off the deep end. And - she spanked the nearest ones to her and I - I and my brother happened to be couple of near ones to her and she just pulled the sheet down and then spanked our b
e
hinds with her hand. She must have had a sore hand. She was like that. And I remember while we were there, it happened at breakfast time, there was a - a man, an Italian I think he was, came round with his dancing bear. Have you ever seen them? Oh. And th
a
t that was a thrill. And they got this - big - quite a tall bear it was. And it - it had a muzzle on and a big chain and he used to play music and he used to just go round and round and round, dancing bear. I can always remember that. And if I see a bear 
I - I think of - the man with his dancing bear and - and Clacton.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Did they take you out in a party onto the beach or did you just play around by yourselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
They always - always went out in a party. We always kept together. We had instructions. Used to get so many - those in charge and - usually girls in charge, looked after you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 But you could play around on the beach?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes, you could play around, you were quite free when you got there. And they had their own shop. Sweet shop, tuck s
hop you see. And - we used to get from home - penny stamps, perhaps a sheet of - not a sheet, but say half a dozen penny stamps which we used to exchange for sweets at the sweetshop, for one penny stamp you used to get a quarter of pound of caramels you k
now and - and all that sort of thing. Strip - a strip of caramels.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 How did you get on this holiday then, was that a club or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Through the church. I think it - had belonged to the Methodist church. Passmore Edwards. And - yes, I - I belie
ve it belonged to the Methodist church and it was through the church we got this holiday. I don't know how long we were there, a week or a fortnight, I can't remember now. I can remember incidents, you know, things that happened.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Can you remember anything else that struck you about 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Clacton{\*\xmlclose} at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No, I - all I can remember of this home is rather high on the - high part of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Clacton{\*\xmlclose}. And - I can't remember - anything - about the beach or anything like that there but - just remember playing ar
ound that's all. With the other boys.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 When you were at church did you ever belong to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, not - never belonged to a choir. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You said that at home you were taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did I say that, we were taught to
 say prayers? I - I remember saying I was saying my prayers but that - I don't think I - yes, we weren't taught. We weren't taught, no. I learnt that more or less at Sunday school. Not - not in the home. No. Yes, I think I - I was saying about we were hav
ing prayers at our bedside and - and this convalescent home at Brighton and I saw that vision. Yes. That - that was really vivid.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You were especially close to that sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. Yes. And that nephew as well. That nephew as well. The same name as m
e, same christian name you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You mentioned your father was a Radical?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 A Radical. Trade unionist and a - a Radical, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Do you know why he was a Radical?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well - I think - I don't know but only - surmise from - later years and I've
 read a bit of history of Ireland that - it was the Liberals who - introduced - Home Rule for Ireland. And - it's in Balfour's time wasn't it? And I think that's why he was Liberal really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 He was a keen supporter of Irish Home Rule was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Do you remember him voting in elections?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. Oh yes. In - in elections and local elections and that. And - there were mostly Conservatives and Liberals then. Sir John Simon was - standing for - I don't know what area i
t was but - but he was standing for someone and Horatio Bottomley for Liberals. And - I forget - we used to sing something about them, vote - vote, vote for Mr Simon, knock old Bottley down the stairs and - do something with him and - he, vote, vote for B
o
ttomley anymore. I can't think of the words now. But - kids used to go round the streets singing that you see. And I can remember all the yellow signs and - yellow - Liberal posters, the blue Conservative posters. Vote for Sir John - no, vote for John Sim
on I think it was then, don't think he was knighted - then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did your father work for him at elections then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
I - well I can't remember him ever - going out as - canvassing or anything like that for him, but - he was - out on some business to do w
ith them very often - at the - at the club - the Liberal club, political club. Yes, some sort of voice. Meetings and that, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 He wasn't on the committee of the club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Not as I knew - not - as I can remember, because - I was quite young then.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did he talk in the home about all this then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well I - I don't know really, he - he could have done but - I wasn't interested, I wouldn't take it in you see. I'm talking about - I would be about eight years of age then, I wouldn't be very intere
sted, but I can remember - those - campaigns at election time. And the person - the colours. Especially the colours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did your mother take any interest or did she just follow him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. Just follow him. Yes. Yes. Don't think she was entitled to any
 views of her own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did she really not have any interests outside the home then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh - no. No. No, all her life was the home - and children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did she have any friends of her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh just friends, yes, oh yes, one special friend Mrs Pitt,
 I remember this Mrs Pitt. She - she'd had some operation on her nose and - she used to speak funny you know and - all used to wonder what she was saying, mother could understand her but we couldn't understand her. What's the matter with Mrs Pitt, you kno
w. I can remember her particularly. Mrs Pitt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 She'd go out to call on her would she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes. And - yes, she'd be round there. We go round there, not very often I don't think, meet her shopping perhaps you know. Go shopping together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 When your parents friends came in they'd get a cup of tea or something?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 But not something to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well remember 'em having a cup of tea and - always a cup of tea going, kettle was always on. Yes, my mother was very fond of tea. Remember - th
e - coalman coming round with a - a - the coal lorry or coal cart rather, an old horsedrawn coal cart. Used to be a shilling a hundredweight. And - my mother used to call out, a hundred please coalman, and I used to think as a kid, how's he going to count
 out all those pieces? I mean, because I though it was a shilling for a hundred piece - a hundred knobs you know, something like that. But - wasn't it cheap then? You couldn't get coal quite easily then. But - shilling a hundredweight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were you going to say something about your mother's friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No. No. I can only remember that one particular friend.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 She didn't go out for a drink ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. Oh no, no. Didn't go out to drink. Not to my knowledge. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You mentioned the greyhound c
oursing, were there any other sports your father took part in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. No, no other sports. Just this greyhound. I think he did it when he was in Ireland. Started it. 'Cos it was a - a - oh almost a national sport in Ireland was greyhound racing. Or whip
pet racing it was, small kind of greyhound a whippet. But that's - that started him off I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would he bet on these greyhounds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh they'd bet, yes, oh yes, they'd bet. Yes, that's what they used to do it for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did your father or mother be
long to any savings clubs like sick clubs and funeral clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
What they call - oh - Christmas club. They used to be run at the pub - I believe they used to call it slate club, I don't know why. I don't if it used to go on a slate - you know, subscript
ions or what, and they used to have a share out at Christmas time. Used to buy things for Christmas. Then. And - I remember that, I remember that what they called a slate club, I know it was a - it was run by a publican, or somebody - somebody - a custome
r
 of the pub. And - they used to have this general share out at Christmas you know. Some of them used to blow it all before they go home you know. Drink it away. But - that was a one. Then - then there was the - hospital Saturday - Society, and that was a 
penny a week, and that - that's a kind of sock club. And that's - and helps you if you have to go into hospital you now and that. Yes. Hospital Saturday Fund. I was thinking there was another one but - can't quite - can't recall it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was there some kind of insurance money when he died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well - I think so, there was an insurance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 So you would have subscribed to that to get that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh - oh yes, an ordinary endowment, life - life insurance. Oh yes. Oh yes, they were all - all insured I mean -
 I was insured from when I was born. You see, for a penny a week. I got the policy out there - not policy, got the book up there, got the policies in there and then when I was fourteen it was increased to tuppence a week well - I got a free policy on that
 
now? I suppose it's not worth the trouble to come to get it so they might as well give me a free policy. It isn't hardly is it. Yes, could insure - baby for - penny a week see. And - then - these - mates and that in his club, you know, the Radical club, t
hey - they had a - collection for - mother, you know, for the widow and - and she got quite a good bit - I can't remember how much it was but I knew at the time, oh what a lot of money. What a lot of money. That was very acceptable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You said you didn't
 get any charitable help at that time, but you mentioned this visit to the Salvation Army?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Salvation Army, yes. Yes, they used to give you food and - that, I don't know if they gave you money but they gave you - your food. Things like that, things to help in the home. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would that be before your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh - oh yes. Oh yes, before he died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Is it just one time you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
That's only one time I can remember - going - there. And - well I - I can't remember going any - any
 other times later in life you know, for - any more visits. But - remember that - special occasion. Mother went, but she used to go - fairly regularly I think. I didn't always go with her you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you feel at that time that she had a tremendous st
ruggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - not at that time, not at that particular time but - I did - I - I didn't know until later on in life that - why she went there. See, I - I - I wrote that down didn't I. I didn't know why she went there but later on - 
as I got older I realized what - a struggle she - she had. That was after I left school you know, I realized what a struggle she had, I don't think it ever entered me head - during \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 from - or until I was fourteen or fifteen - but it was then, af
ter then that I began to realize, and then later on - after she - she'd died I realized it more than - more than ever. What a - struggle she must have had and - how wonderful she was. Really to - keep things going like she did. Must have been a great stra
in on her life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You saw her working so late at night, you mentioned about her hands?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes, that's right. Well - I used to think it was terrible but I - I - I never - you know - thought about it so much as I did later. I used to - feel sorry, you 
know, I knew what it was, she never - she would never say anything about it, but I'd know what it was, cause of it. See. Working. But she'd never murmur. Never heard her moan about that. How she was, you know, hard worked, kept it - absolutely marvellous.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Why was it her hands were bleeding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
With the - the cold weather in the wintertime, you had to use these thread and had to wax the thread, and the wax gets brittle in the cold weather you see. Well as you pull - pull the thread like that it comes
 across your - your fingers like that see. Cuts into the flesh. I've had it the same when - when - I - just the same when I've been working. And my hands are strong you know and - absolutely - you just pull thread like - tight, have to pull it tight, unle
ss - as you pull it tight it catches your hands there you see, cuts the skin. And - don't heal because - you're always at it that it doesn't heal, sore all the times. More like broken chilblains, that's what it feels like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 If she was ill would some neighbour come and help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - do you know, I can never recall her being ill. I can't - can't - cannot - can't think at all when she was ill. Until later on you know. After 1918. Well 1940 really. 1939 - '39 when she died. But - I can never recall her being ill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 So none of the neighbours actually helped in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. No. I remember later on when we got a bit - were a bit better off she used to have a woman help her to do the washing. And - but not - not for long because - she couldn't do 
it like her you know, didn't know how. She wouldn't keep her. You know, she can't do it the way I want - I want it done you know, not properly. They wasn't - wasn't whiter than the whitest you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 When would that be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh that - that was - 
that was during the world - the first world war. We was better off then, we were better off then. Really. And after. And up to - after the war we were better off - really. And me sisters started a - a room of their own you know, workroom of their own and 
- they make a bit of money. Employing - girls.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
In some areas if there was some family that was disapproved of there would be some kind of action by the neighbours, you don't remember anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. Don't remember any quarrels like - like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No rough music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. I - no, I don't remember anything like that. No. No, I - I can't remember anything like that, any rowdyism in the houses or anything of that, no noisy neighbours. Always lived in very - decent neighbourhood - neighbourhoods.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you remember the shopkeepers as being particularly important people?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - the - those - the larger - shopkeepers, the stores, some of them used to have prominent positions in the church and - they were looked up to you know. But - 
there were others, the small shopkeepers, they were quite respected and - and many of them had - you know, positions in the church else on a Council. I don't remember many }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 councillors}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967  but I remember many churchmen and - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was it a different kind of people who went to the church than the chapel?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - I think so. They were more the upper classes who went to the church. Now we used to - very often - take a walk, when we lived in - when we had our shop - used to go round }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 Clapton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 , go up Springfie
ld Park and Stamford Hill - sometimes Sunday evening, this was after I'd left school, and - see people going to church and they'd all be dressed up. Frock coats and - silk hats, you know. Our governor used to be amongst them, or two governors, Mr - the tw
o
 Mr Turner's and - and other people you know, all going to church, all dressed up in top hats and best clothes, white gloves and that. Whereas in the lower church, the chapels and - and non-conformist churches they - they were just ordinary people and wen
t - just in their best Sunday clothes you know, but not made up, not - not all - togged up, no. But - they seemed to be apart. Well I think it is now really. The - the C. of E. and non-conformist. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would the C. of E. clergy call on people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 They would have done. They - oh yes, I think they used to. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You don't remember them visiting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. No. No. Don't remember - don't remember them visiting at all. No. Only - my sisters were Methodist you see, and we were Methodists. And we used t
o - have people call in the house, if - anybody was ill you know, bring us some fruit or eggs or something like that, during the - 'course this was after 1918, the 'flu epidemic, that was the following year wasn't it. There used to be - hundreds - thousan
d
s of people died then, through that. And it was terrible. And - used to get visitors you know, those people who hadn't got it, they just hadn't got it - and come and visit you, bring you eggs or something like that. And then - very often they - they - the
y'd got it next and you'd recovered and you'd go and visit them. Pay back a compliment.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 All those houses you were in were all rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 All rented. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you know any of the landlords?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, I don't - don't remember. Don't remember 
any landlords. No. I know landlords used to come for the rent but - I can't remember - what they were like. Don't remember their names. See. Probably if they'd been extraordinary and - give you a penny or two you'd have remembered them you know but - but 
-
 you thought they were - you termed them as wealthy people really, landlords. Don't know if they were but - don't suppose they were really. Might have been to - point of standards - then. Because - I mean - you could rent a - a big house - quite big house
 for about eight shillings a week. Eight to ten shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you see anything of the policemen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Policemen? Oh - yes, I saw them all right. Oh yes. Yes. We - we used to do it - get up to tricks, daring tricks. And we knew that if we got c
aught that - we'd have a jolly good cuff round the ears you know with a policeman's gloves or his - bare hand. So really - I think we had more guts and - more pluck than the present day children. Present day children will do it and know they won't be puni
s
hed and know the policeman won't clump them don't they. But we knew we'd get a clumping. And - I told you I was - taken to court didn't I? I don't - I don't think I put - I was a juvenile delinquent for a little while, think, yes. Yes, we - when we used t
o
 come out of school we used to go over some wasteground, this wasteground had got a fence all round it but - several holes in the fence where we could get through, used to go this ground and play, you know, cowboys and Indians and all that sort of thing. 
A
nd - there was about - oh, a dozen of us I suppose playing over there and - after school, and there was a factory in the background and some lads in the factory, about aged about sixteen or seventeen, they started pelting us with stones. So we pelted them
 
back. And evidently one of their stones - was thrown over the fence and hit a policeman, hit him in the eye, cut his eye. So - he got through the hole - came after us you see. And most of the boys scrapered, they got away, but there was - me, I was - I wa
s
 the last one there I think. I was trapped on there so - I see this gap in the hedge - in the fence, I make it for this gap. No good you going there he said, going through that gap, there's a policeman the other side. And I believe him. So I waited for to
 
be arrested. He arrested me and there was another one of my pals and me, he said - he came, up, let him go, let him go, he said. You know, and he started fighting this policeman, struggling with him. And then two more policemen came along. So this policem
a
n was holding me, he said - he said to be there others, get that one, he said, he's the one - he's the one I want. And - they did, they got him. And then they caught another one. There was three of us altogether they caught, and - asked name and address a
n
d - you know, we gave our names and addresses and - my father wasn't alive then, which I was - jolly glad in a way, and - anyway - I didn't say anything about it when I got home. Oh they - this boy - who was - a little terror, was annoying the policeman, 
t
hey took him to the police station. And they frog marched him, what they call frog marching, they held his hands and his feet, held - held him face downwards and bumped him all the way up through the churchyard all the way to the police station, bruised h
i
s face, bruised his head. Just to punish him. Knees. And - a day or two after - received a summons - to appear at Old Street Juvenile Court. My mother was upset you know. What - what have you been doing? I said - oh - we got accused of throwing stones but
 
it wasn't our stone throwing, it had come from somebody else you see. She said, oh a good job your dad's not alive, she said, you would go through it. So we had to go up to court. Cut a long story short and - so - we went to - Country Court first, we went
 
to the wrong court, it's a little tiny court you know, I wasn't a bit afraid - going - a man said, oh you've come to the wrong court, you go - go to the other court. Old Street. Shoreditch. So we went there and there was a great big building - lots of ste
p
s up to it like St Pauls you know. Oh I was scared, I though, oh fancy having to go there come here. Anyway we got up the steps - up the steps and went in and we had to wait for our case to come up. Well while we were waiting - there's a boy came out of t
h
e courtroom and - he was held with two policemen, by two policemen, he was screaming and struggling - and that, and - I could imagine myself, you know, being like that. I thought, I wonder - I wonder if they're going to do the same to me as they're going 
t
o do to him, I thought he was going to bet the birch or something. 'Cos the boys at school all said, you won't half get it there, you'll get about four strokes of the birch for that, you know. And so anyway - eventually we came before the magistrate. And 
h
e called out the policeman's name to give evidence, the policeman as a witness to give evidence. And he hadn't appeared. I don't know why, don't know if he'd gone on the sick list or not but I was - oh I'm glad he's not appeared you know, make it easier f
o
r us. So judge said - read out charge, he said, you're charged with throwing stones. Yes sir. Well you know it's wrong to throw stones? Yes sir. Well, he said, the sentence will be - I will - fine you sixpence each, he said, and don't let me see you here 
anymore. Oh weren't we relieved. When we came out the court my mother said, oh come on, she said, we went into a caf\'e9
 and she had a cup of tea and I had a glass of lemonade. To celebrate. But - oh I - I always remember that. Well I would wouldn't I? That's 
the only time I ever appeared in court, but - we were still innocent of it really. But if this boy - hadn't - been so nasty and annoying that policeman I think we'd have got away with it. He - he wouldn't have taken any notice, he'd have let us go. But he
 - he caused the trouble.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 He got off too with the sixpence fine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes, he got off - he got off with his sixpence as well. He was a German boy, Hausman his name was. And - he was a little terror. But he was a favourite in the school although he wa
s - although he was - you know, with teachers, although - he was such a little - vagabond he was really, he was poor, but he was really rough you know. But he could play football. Play good football. And he couldn't do anything wrong with teachers because
 he could play football. He was in the school football team.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you usually play with a group of boys then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. Yes, when we - just after school, we usually - usually split up then and go to - various homes and then perhaps I'd play with me brother, usually my brother. We played together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would there be just boys or would there be a mixed group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well boys usually - usually, but - we did have some girl friends you know in our own - road, our own street. And - I remember two sisters you know who were very sweet on but - used to be - play with them. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What sort of games did you play then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh - hopscotch. Now - piggyback - leapfrog. All that sort of thing you know. Leapfrog and hopscotch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did your mother mind if you got dirty when you were playing out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well, she used to mind but - she used to scold us you know but - we didn't very often get - dirty. Clean streets you know. Pavements you see. Not much chance of getting dirty, unless you went onto some - wastegrou
nd probably you know, but we never used to do that. Not from home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You played in the street near the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Near the house, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You didn't go in the park or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, 'cos we always in - within call - the house in case you were w
anted you know, mother come to the gate, Charlie, come on, I want you to go somewhere, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were you free to play with anybody that you wanted to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes. Oh yes. There was no discrimination.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 There were no children they'd say you mustn't play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh no, mustn't play with them, no. Oh no. Well not - our parents anyway. I think that would be with - with some people - did - go with some parents wouldn't let them play with other children, yes, thought they were below them you know, 
inferior. Not - not very often I don't think that happened.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Apart from the Band of Hope did you belong to any sort of clubs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No. Didn't belong to any clubs. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you have any hobbies as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 I didn't. I didn't have any hobbies.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You didn't collect anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. No. No, I was - rather quiet you know - I didn't do - much at home really. Just - just some - a bit of house - I used to do some housework. I used to be fond of housework really. Scrub the floors - and all 
that. Yes. Oh yes, I often used to do that - for mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You wouldn't go fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - what we called fishing, we used to go sometimes but - used to get the tiddlers down - down by Lee, the River Lee. And - go onto a backwater of the River Lee
. We used to call it the feeder. There's a huge pipe where the - water used to come through into this - stream and the tiddlers used to come through the pipe and we - we'd get a sheet or blanket, ask mother if she'd got an old blanket she didn't want you 
k
now, used to give us something or - a big piece of rage two of us used to go and we used to hold a corner each and hold it under this pipe, and the water used to rush into it, be like a strainer, and leave all the fish in the bag and we chucked them in a 
jar you see. And then they come along - some boys'd come along and smash the jar, something like that you know, with your tiddlers in. Rough boys. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You didn't have a bicycle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What about going out for walk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well - we used to
 go in just a - we didn't used to walk far. Used to go up to the park, Victoria Park was the - nearest park to where we lived in Hackney. That was quite a good walk really. But {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceName}}Speedwell{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} was close at hand and then there were - recreation grounds you k
now. And there was a swing in there, something like that. Only a small - recreation ground like they've got down Morden, little places. And - used to go there sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would you play football?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, I wasn't a - I wasn't at all sports - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 sports minded}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 . No. No. I used to \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 all those games. Never played football. But I'd like to have learned to swim you know but - I - I couldn't stand water on me head really, I used to be frightened to death. Anyway later on - I used to - go - just to get 
out of having school lessons you see. I never used to go in the water. I used to keep in me box, in changing box, 'til - 'til it was all over and then come home then I just had a go at going to washroom and just wet me hair like that you see. Make my hair
 like I'd been in the water. Teacher used to think I'd been in the water.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you have any pocket money as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Not - only what we earnt. Didn't have anything given regularly. If we - wanted any money we had to earn it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Apart from those
 regular Saturday jobs you told me about were there any odd ways of earning a penny at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well if you - yes, you'd just hope, you wouldn't ask for it but you'd - ask Mrs So - and - so if she wanted any errands you see, wanted you to run any e
rrands for her, and - perhaps she would pay you and perhaps she wouldn't. But you wouldn't ask for it. Now - I remember particularly - one occasion when we'd had our photographs taken at school, and they were tuppence - tuppence each to buy as a postcard 
w
ith the whole group of the class on, see. And as - one I particularly liked you know, I'd come out good. So I - you had to order them if you wanted one, so I ordered one, I hadn't got the money. But - you had to order them in - for about - week in advance
.
 So I - so I'll get that money you know in time. And - however I managed to earn a penny. And - I used to go round to my aunt's quite a good bit, that one I mentioned who I used to watch machining all these uppers you know, and she usually used to give me
 
a penny. And - sometimes I felt as though I shouldn't take it. Well I thought to myself, I'll go round to Aunt Harriet's - and - I reckon she'll give me a penny, that'll make me tuppence up see. And so I went round. And - it was the day before supposed to
 
collect the - photograph. So - anyway - I'd been round there some time, and she offered me a penny. And somehow me conscience pricked me, I thought, oh no. I don't think I ought to you know. Don't think I can. And I refused it. See? What, you refuse? What
 
are you refusing money for, never refuse money. So I said, no, that's all right Auntie, I said, I don't want it you know. And I wanted it and I didn't want it. Didn't know what to do. He conscience seemed to prick me somehow. And - so I - I went without i
t
. So - next day - photographs had come, teacher was handing them out, how about yours Mulligan? See. So I said, oh I haven't got the money. You haven't got the money, what did you order it for, you know. You know, you'll have to get the money. So I said, 
w
ell I - I can't. Said, I've only got a penny. So - says, well that don't do, she said, it's tuppence, see. So I said, I'm sorry, I said, I - he said, you try and get it. And I - I never got it. And she was mad with me, I don't know what she did with the p
hotograph, didn't give it to me. I didn't get it. But that was funny that was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You wrote about the day you didn't go to school, was that the only time?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No, I did it - I did it - after that, once after that I think I did. Later on, when I was abo
ut - thirteen. Think it was - that was a woodwork class, I wanted to dodge that. And - we used to have to go to another school for that and I dodged that. I didn't go. But - I got away with it. Because they didn't keep a - record at - the regular school y
ou see. Just knew I was absent for woodwork, I'd gone to - a Leather Lane school for woodwork.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You think that you met this school attendance man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. 'Cos we used to - there used to be a - a school attendance man really, you see they used to 
come round - inquire why a child - hadn't been to school for - well they do now don't they - hadn't been to school for such a - period or - or why they were away a certain day, see. And this man, of course he wasn't a - inspector at all, he wasn't a schoo
l
 board man but he said he was you see. Just to scare me, just having a joke I expect he was you see. And he said, why aren't you at school today? So I said, oh - what was it I said now, I - something - about I was ill or something, got measles. So he said
,
 no, he said, I know, he said, you - you're playing truant, he said. And I'll come round to see your parents about it. He scared me out of me life. But - that was the most miserable morning I ever had I think, that morning. 'Cos I was quite - quite a kid,
 well young when that happened.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You always used to walk to school did you? And then come back midday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes, come home to dinner, two hours for - break, from twelve 'til two, mother used always used to have dinner for us. Nearly always a hot one. Yes. Yes. 'Cos you used to have to do a lot in that - in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
You were in hospital and missed a lot of school, did they give you any lessons in hospital?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No, never had any lessons to make up for it. No. Nothing like that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 How did you spend the day then in hospital, were there any games?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No, well I was mostly in bed. In fact I think I was in bed all the time. Can't remember getting up - only an hour at a time had to get up. 'Cos I know - sometimes I used to go into the other wards, see 
me sister and sometimes she used to come in to me but it was very seldom. Usually - used to be able to see her on - on the ward when we were out on the balconies, on the level with me, but - that was the only time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were the nurses there sympathetic?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes, I mean they were quite nice and - I remember we used to have cold cocoa for breakfast, it was always cold. Used to be a thick skin on top. And - almost cut it you know. But I used to love that. The cream you know all gone cold and congealed. I
t was lovely. And then - I can remember - doctor operating taking a little fluid off me lung and - I had to go in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 anaesthetic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967  you know 'cos wasn't much - they just cut you open a bit and - he said to the nurse, oh there's a fly on him. Just shows you h
ow - how careful they were those days, there's a fly on him. I thought a fly? And - after he done the - taken the fluid away he held the bottle up, oh there it is, look, it's in there. There was this fly floating on top of the fluid. Just imagine that hap
pening these days. 'Cos it's done in - in the bed, in the - in the hospital ward bed, wasn't operating room.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 It must have been terribly painful wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No, I don't think it was. I can't remember having much pain. Perhaps they gave me a local }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 anaesthetic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967  just to - as they cut it open.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 It was suspected T.B. the whole time was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. Yes. Yes. And then they - then they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 diagnosed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967  it as pleurisy. Liquid pleurisy on the lung, fluid you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were you able to have visits from your mother and father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. Oh yes, they used to come. My mother usually, father would never come very often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 How often could she come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 I can't think of - how often. No, I don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would it be roughly once a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes, once a week at least. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Do you remember if you were able to have many of your own things, like a few toys or books or your own clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. All - all hospital things, books and - toys and that, we used to play with them on the hospital floor. All over the floor all that. The ward floor. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Do you think that being removed from your family so often it had any effect on you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No, I don't think so. No. No, I - don't think it affected me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You don't remember feeling miserable in there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No, I don't think - no. Never felt miserable I don't think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did your mother and father show much interest in your work at school or not?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No. Not in my work anyway. No, they - they didn't - I - I remember - I used to stammer ver
y badly. After I had that accident - when I jumped through that window - I had a disorder, St Vitus dance they called it. Twitching. And - then that caused me to stammer. Used to stammer ever so bad. Couldn't read - out loud. Well - when I went to a new s
c
hool - after - after we moved - they said which standard were you in at the old school? I said, standard two. Oh well, we'll take you into standard two and give you a test you see. Well the first test was reading from a book. And being such a nervous stat
e
, you know, being new and that and I was all pent up, and I couldn't get a word out. Oh, my face was red, I was sweating. I felt absolutely terrible. They said, oh you're no good for this class. They put me down in standard one. And that's what happened v
ery often when we - when we changed schools, I was put down because of me stammering. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you get any help for this stammering?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No - no, no, no help at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 It just disappeared did it,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well - I tell you what I - I had that - 
'til - I was about - thirty. Over thirty. Think it was. And - I used to read - to myself and wife said - why don't you - try reading out loud? I said, I couldn't read out loud, I said. Try it, she said, they say it's a good cure, you can cure yourself of 
s
tammering if you do that. So I said, well I'll have a try. So - got a book you know, novel, used to go out for picnics and - we used to go out together and - she used to do her knitting and I used to - read to her. And - I gradually got better, but when I
 
got to a word I got stuck on she wouldn't take a bit of notice, she'd - you know - continue with her knitting, and - she wouldn't let me slip it, the word, but - say it, get it out. And I used to manage it. Overcome it. And gradually - I got all right. I 
g
ot quite - quite good. And sometimes now I - if I get a bit excited I might stammer a bit but nothing - I never thought I'd be able to speak in public you know, and - I knew a chap at Tollesbury and - he was the same. He was worse than me I think. Oh he w
a
s terrible. He could sing - sing lovely, a lovely tenor voice. And yet he used to stammer like that as well. I said to him, why don't you take a course of reading out loud, I said. Come round my house, I said, and - read to me. I couldn't do that you know
,
 he stammered it out. I said, well you try. So - I said, or - I said, read - in front of the mirror. Read a book and - and - in - so you can see yourself and so - imagine somebody else is there and read to 'em, I said, that's another - another way I pract
i
ced to get rid of it. And - he tried it for about two months and I'm sure he was improving, but he gave it up. Still as bad as ever. Yes. Yes. It was very bad for me because - when I first left school getting this job in this warehouse I used to have to a
n
swer telephone. Well, the first time telephone rang when I took over this job the manager said, answer the phone Charlie. And I - oh I went red, you know, I thought to myself, I can't answer the phone, you know, and so I picked up the receiver you know, t
h
 - th-this is number so and so you know, I couldn't get it out. And there's some girls sitting at a - a table working and they were giggling and grinning at me, laughing at me. I got in a terrible state. Anyway - the manager felt sorry for me you see. Sai
d, all right, I'll do it. But - I was all right as I say, conquered it - conquered it. That was remarkable really. People can't believe it when I - say that I used to stammer so bad. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You had three jobs before you left school, how did you get that kind of job?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
I just went to the shop and asked if they wanted anybody. Asked if they wanted a - a roundsboy or - you see, do the rounds or anything like that. Usually I used to ask if they wanted a roundsboy you know, to - take the orders out. The -
 and then you get many jobs chucked in you know. Cleaning and all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you get on with your employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh - got on all right with them. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Do you think you were well treated by them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well - didn't get paid very well really. 
But I suppose - then I suppose I thought it was something. And - better than nothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Were they quite sort of kindly to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. Oh yes, that - they thought they were paying you well you know if they were paying you half a crown a week. Mostly after school and weekends. But - weekend was a long day. Be out nearly to midnight sometimes. They wouldn't allow it now would they?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would you give the money to your mother then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Give it to mother. Yes. Give it all to her. All - whatever it w
as. Usually give me some back. Went out regular.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Later when you were working in the warehouse you gave her the money did you?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. Gave her wage packet just as it was. She give me what, you know, she thought she could - manage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Do you th
ink that having a job when you were at school altered your attitude to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - really - I would rather - although I had this job, I still wished I'd had more schooling, so that I could have got somewhere and got - got decent job you know. 'Cos
 - this was - this job in the warehouse - it seemed, you know, it was good prospects but - there was something I'd like to have done which was signwriting. Wanted to be apprenticed to a signwriter. That was my ambition really. But I never got that. No. My
 brother, he was apprenticed as a carpenter and joiner and he was fortunate and - after father died they couldn't afford it you see. But - I - I used to - always have an ambition to do signwriting. I have now really.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you go to any sort of evening classes after leaving school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No. That's another thing I regret really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 In the warehouse did you have any holidays with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes, always had paid holidays. Used to get - Bank Holidays, all - all paid holidays and - weeks holiday in 
the summer. Yes, week, oh yes. Yes. Used to pay in for a holiday fund as well. They used to have a holiday fund. Oh that's what they called that - Saturday holiday fund, they called it Saturday Holiday fund one and - used to pay in a penny a week for that
. But - it wasn't much but - used to pay fares - if you wanted to go away, anything of that. You could pay in what you liked really, you could pay more than a penny if you liked. Depending what you could afford but - the minimum was a penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What would
 you do in the weeks holiday while you were working at the warehouse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well I - well I only remember going away once and I had a pal who worked in the same factory and - we went to Southend for a week, and - stayed with his aunt, so it didn't cost us 
much. And we had a lovely time there. Both had straw hats and - there was a guard to them, that was a piece of string clipped onto your hat and then clipped into your buttonhole, in case they blew off. If they blew off they dangled down your side you see.
 Oh yes. But we had lovely time. I kept friendly with him for quite a number of years. 'Til I was - don't know what happened to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4726273\charrsid10450967 him}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 He was really a special friend at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. Special friend, yes. Yes. I think he was the closet friend I've
 had really. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was he doing the same kind of work then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
He was cutting out uppers and - the shoe uppers. What they call a clicker. They call 'em clickers because - the noise the knife makes as they - come to the end of a - cut, it click 
- catches in the board, you know, the point of the knife clicks, that's why they call them clickers. Used to see - adverts outside the factories you know for - vacancies, clickers wanted. Machinists wanted, closers wanted. All that. Closers, they were - t
hose who get - uppers prepared for machining, and machinists wanted. Or paste stickers wanted. Heelers and all that sort of thing you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Do you think that starting full time work changed your attitude to life?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Well I suppose it did - really, 
although - I felt as though - there's something to work for, you know, and think - thinking about the future. But - 'course the future didn't turn out so well as expected it would, owing to the - difficulties the country was in, it was difficult times, be
tween 1918 and 19 - and 1930 - 1930. That was a very difficult period, big depression wasn't there, and I was caught in that you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You carried on living at home up 'til the war was ended?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you start spending Sunday differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - used to go out on Sunday you know, started courting one or two girls you know. But - I suppose they were spent differently to what they had been.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You didn't go on going to Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Didn't go - no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 If you were taking a girl out what sort of places could you go to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - on the Sunday take - go out to the forest or - Chingford, out in the country you see and - on the Saturday go pictures and - or else go up the theatre in the West End. I spent a lot 
of money really in the West End theatres and that, being - being a bit extravagant really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 As a schoolboy had you been to the cinema?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh yes. Oh yes, started - going to cinema when the cinemas first came into being. Yes. Yes. The first one was - they called Gale's - Gale's Kinema, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Mare Street
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Hackney. It was a ha'penny to go in there. That's all. Yes. And I can remember almost the first film I saw. And it was the Pit and the Pendulum. By Edgar Allen Poe. Yes. I remember that. That made such a
n impression, it was so horrible, it was a horrible thing, oh dear. And - I can remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 But that would be Saturday afternoon as a schoolboy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
That - that was, yes, but later - later on I'd go - Saturday evenings to the pictures, or Saturday afternoons sometimes, very often go in the afternoon. Sometimes go in the afternoon and go in the evening the same day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
What about the music halls or the theatre as a schoolboy, would you go to that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 As a schoolboy I wouldn't. No. No. After - 
after - I left school I used to - like theatre. Theatre and opera - and that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
No, I think I only went to one - concert, Henry Wood's concert. It wasn't a promenade concert. It was at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11878666\charrsid10450967 Coliseum}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 , Henry Wood Orchestra. And - that's when I was courting, I was with the wife then. That was after 1918 though.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You hadn't met herby 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you start taking any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No. I never took any interest in politics.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 The experience of work didn't m
ake you feel that employers and employees had different interests at that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well it did but - yet politics never entered into - life you know. Thought there was a - I felt there was a gulf between employer and employee. But - because - you know, 
got - felt like that because - during depression when you go to - for a job - wouldn't be an advertised job, you'd just go and ask if they wanted someone, and it was no, no, just push you aside you know and - used to make a terrible impression on your min
d. They didn't want to know you know. But - then that was counteracted once, I remember one place I went to - to ask if they wanted anybody and - he said, oh well, I'll you a trial. That was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Sloane Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}West End{\*\xmlclose}, and - I never knew the place exi
sted before but I went in and - he said - where do you come from? So I told him Hackney. And he said, oh, how did you come? I said, walked. You walked? What for, what did you walk for? I said, I haven't got any money to ride. So he said, oh well, I'll hav
e
 to see about that. So he gave me a - a pair of shoes and - to take home, to do, to make. When I got home I found - they were a different type to what I'd been making. They weren't turned shoes, they were welted shoes and - I'd never made a welted shoe. S
o
 I couldn't tackle them, I hadn't learned how to make welted shoes. So I had to take them back again. So I said, oh I didn't realize they were welted shoes. So he said, oh, he said, I thought you were a welt - welt shoemaker and turned shoemaker. No, I di
d
n't say so. Oh, he said, I wouldn't have let you have them, he said, we haven't go any - any turned shoes, we don't do turned shoes. Do all welted. So he said, I'm sorry, he said. Sorry you had to come back. But I'll make it up to you. So he said, how muc
h
 will it cost for your fares? I told him. He said, here you are, this'll make it up, and he gave - me fare and over, you know. And I felt ever so - you know - I appreciated it so much, I could have kissed him really you know. But you didn't meet many like
 that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did your mother expect to know who you were out with and so on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No - no, never - never questioned. No - who we were out with.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did you have to be in by a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Supposed to be in about ten o'clock you know, unless we 
were - later - later on of course I mean - I was - over age, I could do as I liked. But before that we had to be in. By ten o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You mentioned a girl in Nunhead, how would you meet somebody like that?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 That was a cousin. That's my - mother's sister's daughter. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Do you remember these sort of groups of lads at the street corners, do you remember anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - there was these - these groups of boys - gangs, what I was telling you about. But, you never used to see 
a lot of them. But - they got well known, you know, used to be accounts in the paper about them. But - I - I don't - they used to do damage but not like to the extent they do now. Silly things - and they used to fight amongst themselves, well, not amongst
 themselves, fight other gangs you know. But most of it was that. Just - have a - punch up you know - between 'em. But I - I would - didn't see many.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 When you were between 15 and 18 you didn't belong to any group of boys?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh no. No. I was a loner
 more or less. Well I just had me own - one special mate. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What would you do with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Probably go to pictures and I'd go down to his house and - he lived with his father, his mother was divorced or separated. He was the only - only child. S
o he used to have lots of time on his - he would have had lots of times on his own, his father - used to drink a lot and go out with other women. Didn't have a very good life. And I used to go round his house and we used to have records, play records, and
 
- we used to - buy some cakes before we went in, pastries you know, and some pop, and chocolate, and used to have a jolly good - blow-out you know, usually sick after. But - we used to enjoy ourselves - like that. And - he joined the Merchant Navy. And he
 
used to come home about every month or every six weeks. And he used to get his pay packet you know when he left ship, we used to do - we used to have a right royal time, he used to give me a good time. He'd always buy me presents. It was mostly - plied be
tween here and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname State}}Hamburg{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. He went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Australia{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} once. I think it was once.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 When was it that you started going to church again then, was that much later?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Well - I think it was after I met - you know, just after I met the present wife, that was - not
 - you know - I was getting on a bit then. Nearly thirty then. She - she used to go you know and I used to go with her. Didn't go regularly though. No, didn't go regularly. I only started going regularly since I was - you know, saved, what they call saved
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Would you tell me the story about how you were in Tollesbury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
How we came to Tollesbury? And I came here? Yes. I did tell you some parts. Where did I get up to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 You were saying how the business wasn't doing very well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 That's right. Y
es. Yes. And - how somebody said, we know just the place for you. Oh. Well - however - day we came to Totham was this wise. The business we had at Tollesbury had gone down, losing trade, and - we were looking for a place to live, move to, because we had n
o
tice to quite from our house. And - anyway we tried various means, we put our name down for a council house in Tollesbury, or somewhere. Somewhere near Tollesbury. A housing officer came to me one day, he said, I've got a house for you, if you'd like it. 
S
o I said, where is it? So he said, in Tollesbury. So I said, but you've got a waiting list, there's waiting - people waiting now in Tollesbury for - for a house. So he says, yes I know, he says, but special favour for you, he said, you pay your rates regu
l
arly, he said, never had any trouble with you. So I said, well I'm sorry but I can't accept a favour like that. I said, we haven't got any children, I said, and people with children come first. So he said, oh well, he said, it's up to you. Please yourself
.
 Anyway - we tried various places and couldn't find anything. And so we said well we'll just make it a matter of prayer, we'll just leave it to God. Let him decide - we've tried. So we just - just did that. Well - we used to have - meetings at our little 
c
hurch which we'd opened down in Tollesbury, we used to get guest speakers you see, who used to come to speak, lay preachers. And we had a particular lay preacher who lived at Totham, he came on Sunday and he said, I hear you're moving. So I said, well - w
e
 said, moving, oh we wish we were. So he said, oh I heard a rumour that you were moving. So I said, no, I said, we haven't got anywhere to live. So he said, I know just the place for you. So I said, where's that? So he said - the barn chapel, great Totham
.
 I said, oh there? He said, yes, he says, there's a cottage empty there and they want caretakers. Well - so - Margaret's heart went down - well went bomp, you know, with a thump - when she thought of it, what it was like because we'd just - we'd just rece
n
tly discovered where the Barn - chapel was you see. We'd been hunting for it for along time, we'd heard about it, we'd just discovered where it was, well we came up one day on our tandem and we explored around, we never went in because we couldn't get - d
idn't know the caretaker. But there wasn't a caretaker. And we looked at this cottage and it was real hermits house. Oh it's terrible place. All tumbled - not tumbled down but }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11878666\charrsid10450967 all delapidated}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967  and - we looked through that window, or the window that was there
, and this room was awful. There was no paper on the walls and plaster coming off. And looked terrible, and hadn't been - looked as though hadn't been lived in for about ten years. And when Margaret thought of that oh, she said, what, she said, that cotta
ge. Oh no, she said. So he said, oh well, he said, we'll do it up for you, he said - he said, come and see Mr Moss about it, the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11878666\charrsid10450967 superintendent}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 . So - I said, all right, we will. So - when he had gone that evening Margaret said, we're not going there are y
ou? So I said, yes. I said, we've been making it a matter of prayer haven't we. I said and we asked God to guide us, I said, he's guiding us I believe. So she said, oh yes So - anyway - went and saw Mr Moss. He said, oh we'd like to have you, you see. And
 
- we've been waiting for two years for somebody to take that place, he said, we haven't had anybody come yet. I said, well I'm not surprised really, the condition of it. So I said, you'll have to do something about doing it. Oh yes, he said, we're going t
o
 do it all up, he said, and - and so - I said, now - I said, if we take it, I said, we can't take it unless we get another room. I said, there's only two rooms. That's no good to us. Got to have a decent bedroom. So he said, oh I'll put it to the trustees
,
 he said, and we'll let - I'll let - we'll let you have the - vestry, the existing vestry which is our bedroom now. And so he put that - they put it to the trustees and they decided to let us have that - that room for a bedroom. Well that was all right. S
o
 it all worked out all right. And so - anyway, we used to come up day after - day after day, 'cos I - I wasn't working, I'd sold the business and used to come and do some wallpapering for our home then, in that - no, we didn't do it in - no, we didn't do 
t
hat, not in that other room. We did some here. We did the wallpapering - they prepared the walls and we did the wallpapering. And - we bought some wallpaper to do the - the place, but we didn't get down to it, we had to just put up with - as it was, put u
p
 with it for a time. Anyway - we moved in. And the day we moved in Mr Moss came round and he said - here's the key for the church. He said, it's broken, he said, I'll try and get one cut. He said, it don't fit very well either, you might have a bit of a t
r
ouble opening the church. So I said - oh, I said - I think I've got a key like that. So - I'm almost sure I have. So - I looked in the - toolbox - I knew it was in - in there and it came from the old house at Tollesbury, I changed the lock when I'd got to
 
Tollesbury, 'cos it was such a rotten old lock I changed it over, and I threw the key in me toolbox. So I found it, tried it in the church door and it - fitted perfectly. So I said, there you are, got answer key of all unknown. And - I'm glad. And - then 
we - Margaret settled down, we both settled down and - got place going and - been here ever since.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Was this congregation at Tollesbury already in existence before your own conversion?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 The Tollesbury - place of worship that we had I was telling y
ou had where lay preachers used to come? No, we - we had that given to us by a lady at Tollesbury. It was a - a - small store, and - they - had a shop opposite my shop and her husband and I were very friendly. He was a congregational member. And - I - aft
e
r he died - I promised her I'd clear that out, she wanted it cleared out you see, or cleaned up. So - I said I would do it for her, and I kept putting it off and - one day she said to me, look - when we are you going to do that - store for me, when are yo
u
 going to clean it out, she said, you keep on promising. I said, start next week. So she said, well, if you clear it out, she said, clean it all out, she said, I'll let you have it - and do it up - I'll let you have it for a place of worship, for Pentecos
t
al church. I aid, right-o. So Margaret and I, we got to it, we pulled all the plaster off the walls, used to have a bath every night, used to get filthy there. 'Course and - so - we got a shed, to remove what stock she'd got there, store it in that shed. 
T
his was all done through the headquarters of Pentecostal church you see. And - that is how it became in - came in existence. And that went on there for about five years, after we left it went on for - for two years. And then it all fell away, so - somebod
y else has got it now for a store.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 But you did say you were rather boycotted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Oh yes, by the - by the members of the Congregational church. Oh yes. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Had this lady herself been converted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Almost. Not quite - didn't quite get there.
 But - her husband had I think although he - he never admitted it. But he used to come over to my shop. He used to argue with me you know. Talk and talk and talk and tried to argue and talk about after life, he didn't believe there was an after life you k
n
ow, eternal life. And - she said - told my wife - after he died she said he used to come home he used to say to her, oh I've been having a lovely long argument with Charlie, he said, but I know he's right, he said, but I won't admit it, he said, but I kno
w he's right. And - on the Sunday evening - just before he died - he said - he said, I've seen Jesus, I'm going to Jesus. And he died. So that encouraged her really you know. I think that - she felt as though she - owed - owed something you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was your own conversion due to some preacher coming or something like that?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes, and - and had a - the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Ellam{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Church{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 room, Maldon, Pastor ran a campaign, a tent campaign in - Tollesbury. And - we were both saved through the - through the preaching of - of the word. Well - we didn't realize what salvation meant really. Before. And - we did then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Why had you been going to the Congregational chapel before?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes, well just - it was the done thing really, we thought, you get in the country. It seems to
 be a - done thing to go to church and that's - that's where it ends. Not - not in all cases, I don't mean in all cases, but majority of people just go - because it's the done thing. But - our - there was a very good minister there, he came round and saw 
u
s at - the first Sunday we were there, In Tollesbury, and invited us to - to the church. And we went you see. And I became a member of the church. Well we both did. But I said, what does that mean? To became a member of church? So he said, oh well, he sai
d
, you believe in Lord Jesus Christ don't you? I said - oh yes, I believe there's a Lord Jesus Christ. That's all right then. I said I do. But - I didn't really. I didn't - I didn't believe really, I had doubts. And - we were made members, but when we were
 - the truth was expounded - really to us we both understood, and - I was saved - one night and Margaret was saved two nights after.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 What was your eldest brother's job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 He was a shoemaker. Father taught him the trade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 That was all his life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Did his wife have a job at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No. No. No. Not - no she didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 The next brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Next one, Jim, he - he's apprenticed to a piano trade, piano - manufacturing - first. Then - he - he didn't carry on with that. Failed in that. Then he became an insurance agent. Got tired of that. Then father taught him the trade.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Was he married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Oh he - he did marry, yes. Yes. But his wife never went out to work. No. Then there was John, brother John. He was French polisher. That was his trade, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11878666\charrsid10450967 French}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967  polisher.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 That's the only job he did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
And his wife didn't go to work either. Then there was Edward. But he had - only had one job, shoemaking, father taught him. His wife worked for a time, in bookbinding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 That wouldn't be as a bookbinder?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 No - in - in a factory, doing a part of bookbinding. Machinist really.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 And then the fifth brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
That was Tom. He's a shopfitter. Apprentice and a shopfitter all his life. His wife didn't go out to work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Is there another one then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Thomas. No. No. That's - myself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Which was the carpenter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Thomas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 That is the same as a shopfitter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 
Yes, the same. Yes, they call that shopfitting. Actually - not actual carpenter shopfitting you see 'cos they work in metal as well. Shopfitters.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Then the eldest sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 Sisters. Both in shoe trade. On - machinists. And the other one -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6114892 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 The first one we're talking about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid4026462 CM  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5642262\charrsid10450967 The first one Kate, she's - no, the second one is the machinist
